            {
              "id": "a467b65a-2a72-3b47-8120-537e8009bf88",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability in Variable `f` Modification",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, a potential nil dereference vulnerability can occur when a variable that may be `nil` is dereferenced. In the provided code snippet, the variable `f` is dereferenced by calling `f.Close()`, even when an error occurs during the creation of the file, which could potentially leave `f` as `nil`. This can lead to a runtime panic, causing the program to crash.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to check if the variable is `nil` before dereferencing it. In the provided code snippet, the `f.Close()` function should only be called if `err` is `nil`, indicating that the file was successfully created and `f` is not `nil`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nf, err := os.Create(\"connected\")\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatal(err)\n}\ndefer f.Close()\n```\n\nIn this fixed code, `f.Close()` is only called if `err` is `nil`. The `defer` keyword ensures that `f.Close()` will be called at the end of the function, even if an error occurs later in the code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `os`: The `os` package provides functions for file and process operations.\n- `log`: The `log` package provides simple logging services.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A2:2017 Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8db8b9b3-c83f-345f-af32-2310bced1d45",
              "name": "The title is missing `MinVersion` in the TLS configuration, defaulting to TLS 1.2 in Go 1.22. For general web applications, TLS 1.3 should be the default with all other protocols disabled. TLS 1.0 may be necessary for legacy client support. Add `MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS13` to upgrade to TLS 1.3.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThis vulnerability arises when the `MinVersion` field is not specified in the TLS configuration in Go programming language. By default, Go 1.22 uses TLS 1.2 if `MinVersion` is not specified. However, for general web applications, TLS 1.3 should be the default with all other protocols disabled. TLS 1.0 may be necessary for legacy client support. \n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should explicitly set the `MinVersion` field to `tls.VersionTLS13` in the TLS configuration. This will ensure that your application uses TLS 1.3 by default, which is more secure than TLS 1.2.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in your code:\n\n```go\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs: certPool,\n    MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS13,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This is a built-in Go library for TLS support.\n- `crypto/x509`: This is a built-in Go library for working with X.509 certificates.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ba8907e0-29dc-38ea-902f-e026f9af44ca",
              "name": "Insecure Default TLS Version Due to Missing `MinVersion` Configuration",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `Insecure Default TLS Version Due to Missing MinVersion Configuration` vulnerability arises when the `MinVersion` field in the `tls.Config` struct is not set. This field controls the minimum version of the TLS protocol that will be negotiated. If this field is not set, the Go TLS library will default to TLS 1.0, which is considered insecure due to known vulnerabilities.\n\nThe provided code snippet is vulnerable because it does not set the `MinVersion` field, and it also sets `InsecureSkipVerify` to `true`, which disables SSL certificate verification.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should:\n\n1. Set the `MinVersion` field to a secure version of the TLS protocol. As of the time of writing, TLS 1.2 and 1.3 are considered secure.\n\n2. Do not set `InsecureSkipVerify` to `true`. This disables SSL certificate verification, which can lead to man-in-the-middle attacks.\n\n## Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS12,\n    InsecureSkipVerify: false,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
