            {
              "id": "c200cf39-b157-3c5a-b3d5-ce58ec134e21",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data payload to the client. However, if the payload is not properly sanitized or escaped, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because an attacker can inject malicious scripts into the payload, which will then be executed in the user's browser when the response is received.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and escape any user-supplied input before including it in a response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data that is included in a template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the payload to the response, you should use a template to include the payload in the response. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"html/template\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    t, _ := template.New(\"foo\").Parse(`{{.}}`)\n    t.Execute(w, template.JSEscapeString(payloadJSON))\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `template.JSEscapeString(payloadJSON)` is used to escape any potentially harmful scripts in the payload.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`\n- `net/http`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
