            {
              "id": "f5810769-6a26-3720-b721-9f6b8fae27ff",
              "name": "Potential for nil dereference panic due to modification of `errcode` variable.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference panic. This can occur if the `errcode` variable is modified to be `nil` before the `util.ReturnHTTPError` function is called. In Go, trying to access a field or method of a `nil` value will cause a runtime panic, which can crash the program.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always check if the `errcode` is `nil` before trying to access its fields or methods. This can be done by adding an additional `if` statement to check the `errcode` value.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\ncc, errcode, err = v.getSecret(id, req)\nif err != nil {\n\tif errcode != nil {\n\t\tutil.ReturnHTTPError(res, req, errcode.Status, fmt.Sprintf(\"%s: %s\", errcode.Code, err.Error()))\n\t} else {\n\t\tutil.ReturnHTTPError(res, req, http.StatusInternalServerError, err.Error())\n\t}\n\treturn\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we first check if `errcode` is `nil`. If it is, we return a generic HTTP 500 error with the error message. If it's not `nil`, we proceed as before.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet provided does not specify any library dependencies. However, it seems to use a custom `util` package for error handling and a custom `v` object for secret retrieval. The `fmt` and `net/http` packages from the standard library are also used.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c2e2ae35-a64e-37d2-be2f-867f0a66930e",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure and deprecated due to its vulnerability to collision attacks. In a collision attack, an attacker can generate a different input that hashes to the same MD5 hash as a legitimate input, thereby impersonating or corrupting the legitimate data. This vulnerability is particularly critical in cryptographic protections, where the integrity and authenticity of data are paramount.\n\nIn Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package is used to compute the MD5 hash. If your application uses this package for cryptographic protections, it is vulnerable to collision attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe general advice is to replace the MD5 hash algorithm with a more secure hash algorithm, such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not vulnerable to collision attacks.\n\nIn Go, the `crypto/sha256` and `crypto/sha3` packages can be used to compute the SHA-256 and SHA-3 hashes, respectively.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `crypto/md5` with `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3`. Here is an example of how to compute the SHA-256 hash of a byte slice:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    data := []byte(\"your data\")\n    sum := sha256.Sum256(data)\n    // use the sum...\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `crypto/sha256` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c21ee62a-9783-3154-8cbc-9f13338e6f4e",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform any HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the user input will be executed by the browser.\n\nThis vulnerability is particularly dangerous because it allows an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser or system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data inserted into a template.\n\nAdditionally, you should implement a Content Security Policy (CSP) to restrict the sources from which scripts can be loaded. This can help to prevent the execution of injected scripts, even if an XSS vulnerability is present.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the user-controlled input to the response, you should use a template to safely include the data. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"js\").Parse(`{{.}}`)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(res, js)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `template.New(\"js\").Parse(`{{.}}`)` line creates a new template that includes the user-controlled input. The `t.Execute(res, js)` line then writes the template to the response, automatically escaping any HTML or JavaScript code in the input.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: Content Security Policy (CSP)](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/Content_Security_Policy)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "cbca216e-5639-31f9-8c6c-436ca32c6177",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform any HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the user input will be executed by the browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data that is embedded in the HTML template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing user-controlled input to the HTTP response, you should use an HTML template and the `html/template` package to safely embed the data. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"index\").Parse(\"<html><body>{{.}}</body></html>\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, index)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `{{.}}` is a placeholder for the data that will be embedded in the HTML template. The `template.Execute()` function automatically escapes the data, so any HTML or JavaScript code in the data will not be executed by the browser.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "dc74e737-0a0b-3d03-bc24-52a1b3119fd1",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, an error message is being written directly to the HTTP response. If the error message contains user-controlled data, this could potentially lead to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always HTML escape user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes data when rendering templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"error\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nt.Execute(rw, err.Error())\n```\n\nIn this version, the error message is HTML escaped before being written to the HTTP response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe fixed code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0721e9a5-0c73-3b83-932d-3508cd312261",
              "name": "Consider using ReverseProxy.Rewrite over ReverseProxy.Director to avoid header removal vulnerability.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability in question is related to the use of `ReverseProxy.Director` in Go's `net/http/httputil` package. The `Director` function is used to modify the incoming request before it is forwarded. In the provided code, certain headers are being deleted from the request. This can lead to a vulnerability where important headers are removed, potentially leading to unauthorized access or other security issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, consider using `ReverseProxy.Rewrite` instead of `ReverseProxy.Director`. The `Rewrite` function can be used to modify the request without deleting headers. This can help to avoid the header removal vulnerability.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```go\nimport (\n\t\"net/http\"\n\t\"net/http/httputil\"\n\t\"net/url\"\n\t\"strings\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\tattachURL, _ := url.Parse(\"http://example.com\")\n\n\tdirector := func(req *http.Request) {\n\t\treq.URL = attachURL\n\t\treq.Host = attachURL.Host\n\t}\n\n\trewrite := func(req *http.Request) {\n\t\tfor key := range req.Header {\n\t\t\tif strings.HasPrefix(key, \"Impersonate-Extra-\") {\n\t\t\t\treq.Header.Del(key)\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t}\n\t\treq.Header.Del(\"Impersonate-Group\")\n\t\treq.Header.Del(\"Impersonate-User\")\n\t\treq.Header.Del(\"Authorization\")\n\t\treq.Header.Del(\"Cookie\")\n\t}\n\n\tproxy := &httputil.ReverseProxy{Director: director, Rewrite: rewrite}\n\n\thttp.Handle(\"/\", proxy)\n\thttp.ListenAndServe(\":8080\", nil)\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- net/http\n- net/http/httputil\n- net/url\n- strings\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten 2017 Category A6 - Security Misconfiguration](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A6_2017-Security_Misconfiguration)\n- [CWE-16: Configuration](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/16.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-16",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/16.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-16"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "28d8fffb-9e57-3dd4-ac89-0a2f334e041d",
              "name": "Vulnerability in ReverseProxy.Director due to header removal, use ReverseProxy.Rewrite instead.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability lies in the `Director` function of the `ReverseProxy` package in Go programming language. The function manipulates the request headers, which can lead to security issues such as HTTP Header Injection. This can allow an attacker to inject malicious headers, leading to various attacks such as Cross-Site Scripting (XSS), Response Splitting, etc.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use `ReverseProxy.Rewrite` instead of `Director`. The `Rewrite` function provides a safer way to manipulate request headers. It ensures that only valid headers are included in the request, thus preventing HTTP Header Injection.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the `Director` function with `Rewrite` function as shown below:\n\n```go\nRewrite: func(req *http.Request) {\n    path := mux.Vars(req)[\"path\"]\n    if !strings.HasPrefix(path, \"/\") {\n        path = \"/\" + path\n    }\n    if gURL.Path != \"\" {\n        req.URL.Path = gURL.Path + req.URL.Path\n    }\n    req.URL.Path = path\n    req.URL.Scheme = gURL.Scheme\n    req.URL.Host = gURL.Host\n    req.Host = gURL.Host\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: This is a standard library in Go for HTTP client and server implementations.\n- `github.com/gorilla/mux`: This is a powerful HTTP router and URL matcher for building Go web servers.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-113: Improper Neutralization of CRLF Sequences in HTTP Headers ('HTTP Response Splitting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/113.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-113",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/113.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-113"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e8b39529-005d-3433-ae44-4784e1f69db0",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data byte slice as a HTTP response. If user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always HTML escape user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes user-controlled data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing user-controlled data to the HTTP response, use the `html/template` package to safely render HTML templates. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"safe\").Parse(\"<html><body>{{.}}</body></html>\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(rw, msg)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `msg` is automatically HTML escaped by the `html/template` package.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ecebcf51-942f-3dbd-96af-00bfe74437ec",
              "name": "Hardcoded JWT Token Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded JWT Token Vulnerability refers to the security risk associated with hardcoding sensitive information such as JWT (JSON Web Token) secret keys directly into the source code. This is a common vulnerability in many programming languages, including Go. The risk arises from the fact that if the source code is ever exposed or falls into the wrong hands, the hardcoded secrets can be easily discovered and exploited, leading to unauthorized access and potential data breaches.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, avoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables or secure configuration files to store such information. This way, even if the source code is exposed, the sensitive information remains secure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport (\n\t\"github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go\"\n\t\"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\t// Get the secret key from environment variable\n\tsampleSecretKey := []byte(os.Getenv(\"JWT_SECRET_KEY\"))\n\ttoken := jwt.New(jwt.SigningMethodHS256)\n\ttokenString, _ := token.SignedString(sampleSecretKey)\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, the secret key is stored in an environment variable named \"JWT_SECRET_KEY\". This environment variable should be set in a secure manner outside of the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP JWT Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/JSON_Web_Token_Cheat_Sheet_for_Java.html)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "bb47147b-0923-3163-b32d-e8a13466a725",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, an error message is being written directly to the HTTP response. If the error message contains user-controlled data, this could potentially lead to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always HTML escape user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes data when rendering templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"error\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nt.Execute(rw, err.Error())\n```\n\nIn this version, the error message is HTML escaped before being written to the HTTP response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe fixed code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
