            {
              "id": "340fc301-c5fd-3c66-bfe5-7bbedc98391b",
              "name": "\"Host Key Verification Disabled, Allowing Man-in-the-Middle Attacks\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Host Key Verification Disabled, Allowing Man-in-the-Middle Attacks\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a situation where the SSH client is configured to ignore the host key verification process. This can potentially allow a man-in-the-middle (MITM) attack, where an attacker intercepts and possibly alters the communication between two parties who believe they are directly communicating with each other.\n\nIn the provided code sink, `HostKeyCallback: ssh.InsecureIgnoreHostKey()`, the `ssh.InsecureIgnoreHostKey()` function is used, which means the client does not verify the server's host key, making it vulnerable to MITM attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, the host key of the server should be verified during the SSH handshake. This can be done by using the `ssh.FixedHostKey()` function, which requires the host key of the server. If the server's host key is not known in advance, a callback function can be used to check the host key against a list of trusted keys.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `ssh.InsecureIgnoreHostKey()`, use `ssh.FixedHostKey()` or a custom callback function. Here is an example of how to use `ssh.FixedHostKey()`:\n\n```go\npublicKey, _, _, _, err := ssh.ParseAuthorizedKey([]byte(publicKeyString))\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatalf(\"Failed to parse public key: %v\", err)\n}\n\nconfig := &ssh.ClientConfig{\n    User: \"username\",\n    Auth: []ssh.AuthMethod{\n        ssh.Password(\"password\"),\n    },\n    HostKeyCallback: ssh.FixedHostKey(publicKey),\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `publicKeyString` should be replaced with the actual public key of the server.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- golang.org/x/crypto/ssh\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Configuration](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A6_2017-Security_Misconfiguration)\n- [CWE-295: Improper Certificate Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-295",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/295.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-295"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e7a3ec6c-5206-3a56-81a6-3bb134ba2fbe",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, an error message is being written directly to the HTTP response. If the error message contains user-controlled data, this could potentially lead to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always HTML escape user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes data when rendering templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"error\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nt.Execute(rw, err.Error())\n```\n\nIn this version, the error message is HTML escaped before being written to the HTTP response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe fixed code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "aa0ae53b-8ec1-34f8-b252-73a0ecd52771",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always HTML escape user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes user-controlled data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the vulnerable code:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(d.ResponseMessage)\nerr := t.Execute(w, nil)\nif err != nil {\n    http.Error(w, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `d.ResponseMessage` is treated as a template string, and any user-controlled data within it is automatically HTML escaped by the `template.Execute()` function.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe fixed code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b4954360-fd34-3b03-9892-6e5ff00a10ce",
              "name": "HTTP WebSocket handshake Origin header vulnerability to Cross Site Request Forgery (CSRF) due to unverified origin domain.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe HTTP WebSocket handshake Origin header vulnerability to Cross Site Request Forgery (CSRF) due to unverified origin domain is a security flaw that can occur in Go programming language when the origin of a WebSocket handshake request is not properly verified. This can allow an attacker to send malicious requests from a user's browser to the server, potentially leading to unauthorized actions being performed on the user's behalf.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always verify the origin of a WebSocket handshake request. This can be done by checking the `Origin` header of the request and comparing it to a list of trusted domains. If the origin is not in the list of trusted domains, the server should reject the request.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to verify the origin of a WebSocket handshake request in Go:\n\n```go\nupgrader := websocket.Upgrader{\n    CheckOrigin: func(r *http.Request) bool {\n        // Check if the Origin header is in the list of trusted domains\n        return r.Header.Get(\"Origin\") == \"http://trusteddomain.com\"\n    },\n}\n\nconn, err := upgrader.Upgrade(w, req, nil)\nif err != nil {\n    // Handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `CheckOrigin` function is used to verify the origin of the request. If the origin is not `http://trusteddomain.com`, the request is rejected.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `github.com/gorilla/websocket`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP CSRF Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross-Site_Request_Forgery_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-352: Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-352",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/352.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-352"
                ]
              }
