            {
              "id": "a7e7caba-28ef-3b01-b9a0-f6018219ac3c",
              "name": "Unintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a situation where an attacker can manipulate the control flow of a program, leading to unexpected behavior. This can occur when user-supplied input is used to construct the name of a function or method to be invoked. If the input is not properly validated, an attacker can cause the application to execute arbitrary code, leading to a variety of attacks such as code injection, data leakage, or denial of service.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the use of the `FieldByName` method. This method is used to access a struct field whose name is supplied as a string argument. If the `key` variable is user-controlled and not properly sanitized, an attacker could potentially access any field in the `clusterSecrets` struct.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using user-controlled input to directly access struct fields or methods. If this is unavoidable, ensure that the input is properly validated and sanitized before use. This could involve checking the input against a list of allowed values, or using regular expressions to ensure that the input conforms to the expected format.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\n```go\nallowedKeys := map[string]bool{\n    \"allowedKey1\": true,\n    \"allowedKey2\": true,\n    // add more allowed keys as needed\n}\n\nif _, ok := allowedKeys[key]; ok {\n    secret := clusterSecrets.FieldByName(key)\n    // rest of the code\n} else {\n    // handle error, key not allowed\n}\n```\n\nIn this fixed code, we maintain a map of allowed keys. Before accessing a field in the struct, we check if the key is in the allowed list. If it is not, we handle the error appropriately.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to require any external library dependencies. It uses only features provided by the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A1 Injection](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A1_2017-Injection)\n- [CWE-470: Use of Externally-Controlled Input to Select Classes or Code ('Unsafe Reflection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/470.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-470",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/470.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-470"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "19ca1c6b-42cd-3f03-a485-97ff504abf5a",
              "name": "Unintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnintended Application Control Flow Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a situation where an attacker can manipulate the control flow of a program. This can lead to unexpected behavior, including unauthorized access or privilege escalation. In the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the use of `FieldByName(key)` function. If an attacker can control the `key` value, they might be able to access sensitive information stored in other fields.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should validate and sanitize all inputs, especially those that can influence the control flow of your application. Avoid using user-controlled data to determine the control flow of your application. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `FieldByName(key)`, consider using a switch-case or if-else statements to control the flow of your application. This way, you can ensure that only expected values are processed. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nswitch key {\ncase \"expectedKey1\":\n    secret = status.expectedKey1\ncase \"expectedKey2\":\n    secret = status.expectedKey2\ndefault:\n    // Handle unexpected keys\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the required library dependencies. However, the `FieldByName` function is typically used with the `reflect` package in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-807: Reliance on Untrusted Inputs in a Security Decision](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/807.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-807",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/807.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-807"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e50671f7-9d64-3a29-87aa-d8655e15127a",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic purposes as it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, making it possible for an attacker to craft a malicious input that produces the same hash as a legitimate input. This can lead to a variety of security vulnerabilities, such as password cracking, data integrity attacks, and more.\n\nIn the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package provides functions to compute MD5 hashes. If your application uses this package to compute hashes for cryptographic purposes, it may be vulnerable to the aforementioned attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should replace the MD5 hash algorithm with a more secure hash algorithm, such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not susceptible to hash collisions.\n\nIn Go, you can use the `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3` packages to compute SHA-256 or SHA-3 hashes, respectively.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can replace the MD5 hash algorithm with SHA-256 in your code:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n    \"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    hasher := sha256.New()\n    hasher.Write([]byte(time.Now().String()))\n    uniqueIdentifier := hex.EncodeToString(hasher.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n- `time`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "4016f6f0-a1c5-30da-8558-29d4322fad89",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if the response data is not properly sanitized or escaped, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because an attacker can inject malicious scripts into the response data, which will then be executed in the user's browser when the response is received.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and escape any user-supplied input before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data that is included in a template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the response data using `http.ResponseWriter.Write()`, you should use the `html/template` package to create a template and then execute the template with the response data. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"response\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(rw, response)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `{{.}}` in the template is a placeholder for the response data. When the template is executed with the response data, the data is automatically escaped, preventing any potential XSS attacks.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go, so no additional installation is required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "67eea4ab-393f-3e06-a58b-c3a5668c3f41",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If this function is used to directly write user-controlled input without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always HTML escape user-controlled input before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes user-controlled input when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing user-controlled input to the HTTP response, use the `html/template` package to render an HTML template with the user-controlled input. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"template\").Parse(\"<div>{{.}}</div>\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(rw, userControlledInput)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `userControlledInput` is the user-controlled input that is being written to the HTTP response. The `html/template` package automatically escapes this input when rendering the template.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e2660010-12c8-3bdc-b861-36e4a7ba8b64",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure practice of hardcoding sensitive information, such as session or cookie secrets, directly into the source code. This can lead to a variety of security issues, including unauthorized access and session hijacking, as an attacker who gains access to the source code can easily retrieve these secrets.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables or secure configuration files to store this information. This not only makes your application more secure, but also more flexible, as you can easily change these values without having to modify and recompile your source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret directly into the source code, you can retrieve it from an environment variable like so:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// ...\n\ntokenSecret.Data[\"user-id\"] = []byte(os.Getenv(\"SECRET\"))\n```\n\nIn this example, `SECRET` is an environment variable that contains the secret. You can set this variable in your environment before running your application.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not appear to require any specific library dependencies.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "04f0dd42-f63d-3836-87c4-418cba482468",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic purposes as it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, making it possible for an attacker to craft a malicious input that produces the same hash as a legitimate input. This can lead to a variety of security vulnerabilities, such as password cracking, data integrity attacks, and more.\n\nIn the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package provides functions to compute MD5 hashes. If your application uses this package to compute hashes for cryptographic purposes, it may be vulnerable to the aforementioned attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should replace the MD5 hash algorithm with a more secure hash algorithm, such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not susceptible to hash collisions.\n\nIn Go, you can use the `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3` packages to compute SHA-256 or SHA-3 hashes, respectively.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can replace the MD5 hash algorithm with SHA-256 in your code:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n    \"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    hasher := sha256.New()\n    hasher.Write([]byte(time.Now().String()))\n    uniqueIdentifier := hex.EncodeToString(hasher.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n- `time`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
