            {
              "id": "603f40f1-f6f6-3a88-bf1a-03555e9d887f",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" vulnerability refers to the situation where a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the `Secure` field of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `isSecure`, which might be `false` depending on the context. If `Secure` is `false`, the cookie can be transmitted over unencrypted connections, which makes it vulnerable to interception and theft.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` field to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which encrypts the data and prevents it from being easily intercepted.\n\nAlso, consider setting the `SameSite` attribute to `Strict` or `Lax` to prevent the cookie from being sent in cross-site requests, which can help protect against cross-site request forgery (CSRF) attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     cookieName,\n\tValue:    \"\",\n\tSecure:   true, // Always secure\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tMaxAge:   -1,\n\tExpires:  cookieUnsetTimestamp,\n\tSameSite: http.SameSiteStrictMode, // Prevents the cookie from being sent in cross-site requests\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code depends on the `net/http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [OWASP - SameSite](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#samesite-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a7920337-90bd-38c7-b457-4aa2a387e240",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure practice of hardcoding sensitive information such as secret keys, passwords, or any other secret material directly into the source code. This is a security risk as it exposes the secret material to anyone who has access to the source code. In the context of session or cookie management, this could potentially allow an attacker to forge session or cookie data.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding secret keys or any other sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables or external configuration to store such information. This not only improves security but also makes your application more flexible and easier to configure in different environments.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret key in the source code, you can use an environment variable to store the secret key. Here is how you can do it:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    sampleSecretKey := os.Getenv(\"SECRET_KEY\")\n    if sampleSecretKey == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"SECRET_KEY is required\")\n    }\n    // rest of the code\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `os.Getenv(\"SECRET_KEY\")` fetches the value of the `SECRET_KEY` environment variable. If the `SECRET_KEY` environment variable is not set, the application will terminate with an error message.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It only uses the `os` package which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secret](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "221c2c0e-ad39-3fd5-8409-df0b22b15002",
              "name": "\"Loading Session/Cookie Secret Material from Secret Management or Environment Instead of Hardcoding in Source Code\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the vulnerability of \"Loading Session/Cookie Secret Material from Secret Management or Environment Instead of Hardcoding in Source Code\" arises when sensitive data such as session or cookie secrets are hardcoded in the source code. This is a security risk as it exposes the secret material to anyone who has access to the source code, making it easier for attackers to gain unauthorized access to the system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to load secret material from a secure secret management system or from environment variables. This ensures that the secret material is not exposed in the source code and can be managed securely and separately from the codebase.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret material in the source code like this:\n\n```go\ntokenSecret.Data[\"enabled\"] = []byte(\"false\")\n```\n\nYou should load it from an environment variable or a secret management system. Here is an example of how to load it from an environment variable:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\nfunc main() {\n    tokenSecret := os.Getenv(\"TOKEN_SECRET\")\n    if tokenSecret == \"\" {\n        log.Fatal(\"TOKEN_SECRET is not set\")\n    }\n    // Use tokenSecret\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `TOKEN_SECRET` environment variable should be set to the secret material. This way, the secret material is not exposed in the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A2: Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "cecd7098-b8bc-3ff0-8567-7842ac727752",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `http.Cookie` struct is used to create a cookie without the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` fields set to `true`. The `Secure` field ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted in transit. The `HttpOnly` field prevents the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, mitigating the risk of cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` fields to `true` when creating a cookie. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over secure connections and cannot be accessed through client-side scripts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in your code:\n\n```go\nr.AddCookie(&http.Cookie{\n\tName:     tokens.CookieName,\n\tValue:    bearerToken,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the `http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "e7ce9c0a-2789-3d2e-8401-2e4f68c30d4b",
              "name": "The title is missing `MinVersion` in the TLS configuration, defaulting to TLS 1.2 in Go 1.22. For general web applications, TLS 1.3 should be the default with all other protocols disabled. TLS 1.0 may be necessary for legacy client support. Add `MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS13` to upgrade to TLS 1.3.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability arises from the lack of a `MinVersion` specification in the TLS configuration in Go programming language. By default, Go 1.22 defaults to TLS 1.2. However, for general web applications, TLS 1.3 should be the default with all other protocols disabled. TLS 1.0 may be necessary for legacy client support. If the `MinVersion` is not specified, it could potentially allow for less secure connections.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to explicitly set the `MinVersion` in the TLS configuration to TLS 1.3. This ensures that the application will not accept connections using protocols less secure than TLS 1.3.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\ntlsConfig = &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs:            caPool,\n    InsecureSkipVerify: false,\n    ServerName:         server,\n    MinVersion:         tls.VersionTLS13,\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS13` has been added to the TLS configuration to ensure that the minimum version of TLS used is 1.3.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library to execute properly:\n\n- `crypto/tls`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
