            {
              "id": "3cad5a5a-3ebf-34eb-a895-741cbf9df8dc",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and encode user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically encodes data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing user-controlled data to the HTTP response, use the `html/template` package to render an HTML template with the user-controlled data:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"userOrgs\").Parse(\"<div>{{.}}</div>\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, userOrgs)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `{{.}}` is a placeholder for the user-controlled data. The `html/template` package automatically encodes the data, preventing XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f3a80b88-6a02-3360-9685-492f363f76d7",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always HTML escape user-controlled input before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes user-controlled input when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code fix for the specific vulnerability sink:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"safe\").Parse(`{{.}}`)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, org1Teams)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `t.Execute(w, org1Teams)` writes the `org1Teams` data to the HTTP response, but it is automatically HTML escaped by the `html/template` package.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "69beecc4-ed50-35bf-b535-a76a8d7b226b",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, `w.Write(org2Teams)` directly writes the `org2Teams` variable to the HTTP response without any HTML escaping. If `org2Teams` contains user-controlled input, this could lead to an XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always HTML escape user-controlled input before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes all data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"safe\").Parse(string(org2Teams))\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, nil)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `template.New(\"safe\").Parse(string(org2Teams))` creates a new HTML template with the content of `org2Teams`, and `t.Execute(w, nil)` writes the template to the HTTP response. The `html/template` package automatically HTML escapes all data in the template, preventing XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`: for HTML escaping and template rendering.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
