            {
              "id": "d917a063-93c8-314d-ac6a-3b588d8842a2",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS Configuration, Defaulting to Lower TLS Version",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Missing `MinVersion` in TLS Configuration, Defaulting to Lower TLS Version\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the situation where the `MinVersion` field in the `tls.Config` struct is not set. This field controls the minimum version of the TLS protocol that will be negotiated. If this field is not set, the Go TLS library will default to a lower version of TLS, potentially TLS 1.0 or 1.1, which are considered insecure and deprecated.\n\nThis vulnerability can lead to downgrade attacks, where an attacker forces the communication to use an older, less secure version of TLS, making it easier to break the encryption and access the sensitive data being transmitted.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always set the `MinVersion` field in the `tls.Config` struct to a secure version of TLS. As of the time of writing, TLS 1.2 and 1.3 are considered secure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can set the `MinVersion` field to TLS 1.2 in your code:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\nTLSClientConfig: &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs:      pool,\n    Certificates: certs,\n    MinVersion:   tls.VersionTLS12,\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2a9883f4-d507-334b-afed-7bb8ea0aff5e",
              "name": "\"Loading Session/Cookie Secret Material from Secret Management or Environment Instead of Hardcoding in Source Code\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, a common security vulnerability is the hardcoding of sensitive information such as session/cookie secret material directly in the source code. This is a bad practice as it exposes the sensitive information to anyone who has access to the source code. This can lead to unauthorized access, data breaches, and other security issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe recommended way to handle sensitive information is to store it in a secure environment variable or a secret management system. This way, the sensitive information is not exposed in the source code and can only be accessed through the environment or secret management system.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret directly in the source code:\n\n```go\nsecret.Data[\"token\"] = []byte(\"new-token-value\")\n```\n\nYou should load it from an environment variable or a secret management system:\n\n```go\ntoken := os.Getenv(\"TOKEN\")\nif token == \"\" {\n    log.Fatal(\"TOKEN environment variable not set\")\n}\nsecret.Data[\"token\"] = []byte(token)\n```\n\nIn this example, the `os` package is used to retrieve the value of the `TOKEN` environment variable.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe `os` package is part of the standard library in Go, so no additional library dependencies are required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten 2017: A2:2017-Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "5144cdc0-992c-3340-9ff0-d8f8634467e2",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a raw HTTP response to a client. If user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper HTML escaping, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always escape user-controlled data before including it in an HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the user-controlled data to the HTTP response, you should use an HTML template to render the response. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"response\").Parse(tc.mockResponse)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, data)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `tc.mockResponse` is a string that defines an HTML template, and `data` is a struct that contains the data to be included in the response. The `template.Execute()` function automatically escapes the data before including it in the response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
