            {
              "id": "8e56bc40-d3b9-3bde-9655-7d4392762335",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal a user's session cookie and impersonate them.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `isSecure`, which may not always be `true`. If `isSecure` is `false`, the cookie will be transmitted over unsecured HTTP connections, making it vulnerable to interception and theft.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only transmitted over secure HTTPS connections. Additionally, consider setting the `HttpOnly` attribute to `true` to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, further reducing the risk of theft.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```go\npkceCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     pkceVerifierCookieName,\n\tValue:    \"\",\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tExpires:  time.Now().Add(time.Second * -10),\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: for the `http.Cookie` struct.\n- `time`: for the `time.Now` function and `time.Second` constant.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "000bc7df-02e1-3ba6-8298-fd9499bdbb4a",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure practice of hardcoding sensitive information such as session or cookie secrets directly into the source code. This can lead to serious security issues as it exposes the secret material to anyone who has access to the source code, making it easier for attackers to exploit the system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables or secure configuration files to store this information. This not only makes your application more secure, but also more flexible as you can change the secret material without having to modify and recompile the source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret material directly into the source code, you can use an environment variable to store this information. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// ...\n\nsecret.Data[\"value\"] = []byte(os.Getenv(\"KUBECONFIG_SECRET\"))\n```\n\nIn this example, `KUBECONFIG_SECRET` is an environment variable that stores the secret material. You can set this environment variable in your server's configuration.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b7abe607-fb7d-33ed-ae6d-089edd8806a0",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nHardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure practice of hardcoding sensitive information such as session or cookie secrets directly into the source code. This can lead to serious security issues as it exposes the secret material to anyone who has access to the source code, making it easier for attackers to exploit the system.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hardcoding sensitive information directly into the source code. Instead, use environment variables or secure configuration files to store this information. This not only makes your application more secure, but also more flexible as you can change the secret material without having to modify and recompile the source code.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret material directly into the source code, you can use an environment variable to store this information. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// ...\n\nsecret.Data[\"value\"] = []byte(os.Getenv(\"KUBECONFIG_SECRET\"))\n```\n\nIn this example, `KUBECONFIG_SECRET` is an environment variable that stores the secret material. You can set this environment variable in your server's configuration.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies to execute properly.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secrets](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
