            {
              "id": "2811b326-154d-33a3-a2ee-ea62e9ee36a0",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct is set to `false` or not set at all. The `Secure` attribute ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted by an attacker.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over secure connections. Additionally, consider setting the `HttpOnly` attribute to `true` to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, further reducing the risk of attacks such as cross-site scripting (XSS).\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\npkceCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     pkceVerifierCookieName,\n\tValue:    value,\n\tSecure:   true, // Always set Secure to true\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tExpires:  time.Now().Add(time.Minute * 10),\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: for the `http.Cookie` struct.\n- `time`: for the `time.Now` function and `time.Minute` constant.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a76d5a54-7671-31c8-b881-9461d24f3bf6",
              "name": "\"Loading Session/Cookie Secret Material from Secret Management or Environment Instead of Hardcoding in Source Code\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, a common security vulnerability is the hardcoding of sensitive information such as session/cookie secret material directly in the source code. This is a bad practice as it exposes the sensitive information to anyone who has access to the source code. This can lead to unauthorized access, data breaches, and other security issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe recommended way to handle sensitive information is to store it in a secure environment variable or a secret management system. This way, the sensitive information is not exposed in the source code and can only be accessed through the environment or secret management system.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hardcoding the secret directly in the source code:\n\n```go\nsecret.Data[\"token\"] = []byte(\"new-token-value\")\n```\n\nYou should load it from an environment variable or a secret management system:\n\n```go\ntoken := os.Getenv(\"TOKEN\")\nif token == \"\" {\n    log.Fatal(\"TOKEN environment variable not set\")\n}\nsecret.Data[\"token\"] = []byte(token)\n```\n\nIn this example, the `os` package is used to retrieve the value of the `TOKEN` environment variable.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe `os` package is part of the standard library in Go, so no additional library dependencies are required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten 2017: A2:2017-Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "69605ccc-fe50-3768-a0c0-bb8581f293fb",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` attributes of the `http.Cookie` struct are not properly set. The `Secure` attribute ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted in plaintext over an unencrypted HTTP connection. The `HttpOnly` attribute prevents the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, mitigating the risk of cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, ensure that the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` attributes of the `http.Cookie` struct are always set to `true`. This will ensure that the cookie is only sent over secure connections and cannot be accessed through client-side scripts.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the corrected code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     IDTokenCookie,\n\tValue:    token,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `net/http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "48d07369-0b72-3e87-9cdb-2e5748e97ab8",
              "name": "Unspecified IP Address Vulnerability Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unspecified IP Address Vulnerability Detected\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the situation where a network service is set to listen on all available network interfaces (0.0.0.0 or ::), instead of binding to a specific IP address. This can expose the service to unnecessary risk if it is accessible from untrusted networks.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `net.Listen(\"tcp\", \":0\")` function call is binding to all available network interfaces, which can potentially expose the service to untrusted networks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to bind the service to a specific IP address. If the service is intended to be accessed only from the same machine, bind it to localhost (127.0.0.1 or ::1). If the service is intended to be accessed from other machines on the same network, bind it to the specific IP address of the machine.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nlistener, err := net.Listen(\"tcp\", \"127.0.0.1:0\") // bind to localhost and choose any available port\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet only requires the standard \"net\" package, which is included in the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-200: Information Exposure](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-200",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/200.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-200"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
