            {
              "id": "c3e92da4-0cd6-3cde-9b32-081b792b2cf3",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" vulnerability refers to the situation where a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when a cookie is created without the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` flags. The `Secure` flag ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, preventing it from being intercepted in plaintext over an unencrypted HTTP connection. The `HttpOnly` flag prevents the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, mitigating the risk of cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` and `HttpOnly` flags when creating a cookie. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over secure connections and cannot be accessed via client-side scripting.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nreq.AddCookie(&http.Cookie{\n    Name:     \"R_OIDC_ID\",\n    Value:    \"test-id-token\",\n    Secure:   true,\n    HttpOnly: true,\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example does not require any external library dependencies. It uses the built-in `net/http` package of the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "52c1fabf-a760-3501-a448-8f080a437076",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper HTML escaping, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always escape user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code fix for the specific vulnerability sink:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"safe\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nt.Execute(w, resp.user)\n```\n\nIn this code, the `template.New()` function is used to create a new HTML template. The `template.Parse()` function is then used to parse a string into the template. Finally, the `template.Execute()` function is used to execute the template, writing the output to the HTTP response. The `template.Execute()` function automatically escapes any data passed into it, preventing XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d37c618b-9034-34a4-a869-df22e52c09a6",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" vulnerability refers to the situation where a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the `Secure` attribute of the cookie is set to `isSecure`, which might be `false` depending on the context. If `isSecure` is `false`, the cookie can be transmitted over unsecured HTTP connections, making it vulnerable to interception and theft.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of cookies to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which encrypts the data and prevents it from being intercepted.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     \"R_SESS\",\n\tValue:    rToken.ObjectMeta.Name + \":\" + unhashedTokenKey,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet does not appear to have any external library dependencies. It uses the built-in `http` package of Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
