            {
              "id": "327910ab-2b38-3992-ba31-88ec1433b93f",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" vulnerability refers to the situation where a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal a user's session cookie and impersonate them.\n\nIn the provided Go code, the `Secure` attribute of the cookie is set to `true` only if the `Secure` field of the `c` object is `true` or if the scheme of the request URL is \"https\". This means that if neither of these conditions is met, the cookie will be sent over an unsecured connection, making it vulnerable to interception.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of cookies to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which encrypts the data and prevents it from being intercepted.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nhttp.SetCookie(w, &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     stateCookiePrefix + id,\n\tValue:    value,\n\tMaxAge:   int(saml.MaxIssueDelay.Seconds()),\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tPath:     path,\n})\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following libraries:\n\n- `net/http`: This is a standard library in Go for HTTP client and server implementations.\n- `github.com/crewjam/saml`: This library is used for working with SAML, a standard for exchanging authentication and authorization data.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Session Management Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "efcb3a48-b942-3064-b6a1-b5ee16042e99",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal the session cookie and impersonate the user.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct is not set to `true`. The `Secure` attribute ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which is a secure protocol. If this attribute is not set, the cookie can be sent over HTTP, which is not secure and can be intercepted by attackers.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of the `http.Cookie` struct to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS. Additionally, consider using the `HttpOnly` attribute to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, which can help prevent cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nhttp.SetCookie(w, &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     c.Name,\n\tDomain:   c.Domain,\n\tValue:    value,\n\tMaxAge:   int(maxAge.Seconds()),\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n\tSecure:   true,\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n})\n```\n\nIn this code, the `Secure` attribute is always set to `true`, regardless of the scheme of the request URL.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `net/http` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1ccb1a1e-545c-3e34-b082-b4eceb865cb6",
              "name": "User-Input Crafted HTTP Redirect Vulnerability Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"User-Input Crafted HTTP Redirect Vulnerability Detected\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when an application accepts user-controlled input that specifies a link to an external site, and uses that link in a Redirect call. This could allow an attacker to craft a malicious URL that redirects users to a malicious site, leading to phishing attacks, session theft, or forcing the user to perform unwanted actions.\n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when using the `http.Redirect` function with a user-controlled input as the URL to redirect to.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to validate user input before using it in a redirect function. This can be done by checking if the URL belongs to a list of trusted URLs, or by verifying that the URL does not lead to an external site.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple way to validate the URL before redirecting:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"net/http\"\n    \"net/url\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    redirectURL := r.URL.Query().Get(\"redirectURL\")\n    parsedURL, err := url.Parse(redirectURL)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(w, \"Invalid URL\", http.StatusBadRequest)\n        return\n    }\n    if parsedURL.Host != \"\" && parsedURL.Host != r.Host {\n        http.Error(w, \"External redirects not allowed\", http.StatusForbidden)\n        return\n    }\n    http.Redirect(w, r, redirectURL, http.StatusFound)\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, we parse the URL and check if the host is either empty (meaning it's a relative URL) or the same as the request's host. If it's not, we return an error instead of redirecting.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following standard library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`\n- `net/url`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-601",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-601"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "98a93c45-0dd5-3fcd-9bf4-b3bf35d56405",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform any HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the user input will be executed by the browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data that is embedded in the HTML template.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to fix the vulnerability in the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"someTemplate\").Parse(\"{{.}}\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, buf)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `template.Execute()` function is used instead of `http.ResponseWriter.write()`. This function automatically escapes any data that is embedded in the HTML template.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go, so no additional installation is required.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f5ed21ce-ef3b-31c1-95d0-e2d2596c9cd1",
              "name": "JWT Token Vulnerability Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"JWT Token Vulnerability Detected\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a security flaw where an attacker can forge a JWT (JSON Web Token) by exploiting weak keys or algorithms, or by taking advantage of implementation flaws in the JWT library. This can lead to unauthorized access to sensitive information or functionality.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, follow these general guidelines:\n\n1. **Use strong keys**: Always use a strong key that is not easily guessable or brute-forceable. The key should be long and random enough to resist these attacks.\n\n2. **Use secure algorithms**: Avoid using weak or insecure algorithms. For example, avoid using 'none' as the algorithm.\n\n3. **Validate tokens**: Always validate the JWT on the server side. Check the signature to ensure that the token has not been tampered with.\n\n4. **Handle errors**: Properly handle errors related to JWT processing. Do not ignore or suppress these errors.\n\n5. **Keep libraries up-to-date**: Always use the latest version of JWT libraries as they may contain important security fixes.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nWithout the original source code, it's hard to provide a specific fix. However, here is a general example of how to properly handle JWT in Go:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go\"\n\t\"log\"\n\t\"time\"\n)\n\nvar mySigningKey = []byte(\"strongrandomkey\")\n\nfunc GenerateJWT() (string, error) {\n\ttoken := jwt.New(jwt.SigningMethodHS256)\n\n\tclaims := token.Claims.(jwt.MapClaims)\n\n\tclaims[\"authorized\"] = true\n\tclaims[\"user\"] = \"John Doe\"\n\tclaims[\"exp\"] = time.Now().Add(time.Minute * 30).Unix()\n\n\ttokenString, err := token.SignedString(mySigningKey)\n\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tlog.Fatalf(\"Something Went Wrong: %s\", err.Error())\n\t\treturn \"\", err\n\t}\n\n\treturn tokenString, nil\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, we are using a strong key (`mySigningKey`) and a secure algorithm (`HS256`). We are also setting an expiration time for the token.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\n- github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP JWT Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/JSON_Web_Token_Cheat_Sheet_for_Java.html)\n- [CWE-347: Improper Verification of Cryptographic Signature](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/347.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-347",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/347.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
