            {
              "id": "748800b9-3f32-3847-a075-4b8fca17b4cc",
              "name": "Detected Hard-Coded Credential Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nDetected Hard-Coded Credential Vulnerability refers to the insecure practice of embedding plaintext credentials directly within the source code. This vulnerability can lead to unauthorized access if the source code is ever exposed, as the credentials are easily readable. In the provided Go code, the `sampleSecretKey` is hard-coded, which is a security risk.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nAvoid hard-coding credentials in your source code. Instead, use environment variables, configuration files, or secure vault systems to store and access sensitive information. These methods allow you to keep your credentials out of the codebase and make it easier to rotate them if necessary.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of hard-coding the secret key, you can use an environment variable to store it. Here's how you can do it in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    token := jwt.New(jwt.SigningMethodHS256)\n    secretKey := os.Getenv(\"SECRET_KEY\")\n    tokenString, _ := token.SignedString([]byte(secretKey))\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `os.Getenv(\"SECRET_KEY\")` retrieves the secret key from the environment variable `SECRET_KEY`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library:\n\n- `github.com/dgrijalva/jwt-go`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Hardcoded Secret](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hardcoded-secrets)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f9551785-dadd-39bc-9149-a24b61caf70d",
              "name": "Unsecured Session Cookie Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"Unsecured Session Cookie Detected\" is a vulnerability that occurs when a web application does not properly secure its session cookies. This can lead to potential attacks such as session hijacking, where an attacker can steal a user's session cookie and impersonate them. In the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `Secure` attribute of a cookie is set to `false` or not set at all, which means the cookie can be transmitted over unsecured HTTP connections.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always set the `Secure` attribute of cookies to `true`. This ensures that the cookie is only sent over HTTPS, which is a secure protocol. Additionally, consider setting the `HttpOnly` attribute to `true` to prevent the cookie from being accessed through client-side scripts, which can help prevent cross-site scripting (XSS) attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the provided code:\n\n```go\ntokenCookie := &http.Cookie{\n\tName:     CookieName,\n\tValue:    token.ObjectMeta.Name + \":\" + unhashedTokenKey,\n\tSecure:   true, // Always set Secure to true\n\tPath:     \"/\",\n\tHttpOnly: true,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code does not appear to have any external library dependencies. It uses the built-in `http` package of the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - SecureFlag](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#secure-attribute)\n- [OWASP - HttpOnly](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Session_Management_Cheat_Sheet.html#httponly-attribute)\n- [CWE-614: Sensitive Cookie in HTTPS Session Without 'Secure' Attribute](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-614",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/614.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-614"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ef2f8fef-9ddb-3618-9ae2-9b7e4b018cbd",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability due to Modification of `user` Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn the provided Go code, there is a potential nil dereference vulnerability due to the modification of the `user` variable. This vulnerability occurs when the `user` object is null, and the program tries to access its `Name` property. This can happen when the `Get` method of `userCache` returns an error, which means that the `user` object is not successfully retrieved and is therefore null. When the code subsequently tries to access `user.Name`, it will cause a runtime panic due to nil dereference.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always check if an object is null before trying to access its properties. In this case, you should check if `user` is null before trying to access `user.Name`. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```go\nuser, err := l.userCache.Get(attribs.Name)\nif err != nil {\n\t// In a highly unlikely event of having userattribute without a corresponding user object\n\t// we don't want the caller to spin indefinitely. There is nothing we can do about it,\n\t// other than to log the error and move on.\n\tif apierrors.IsNotFound(err) {\n\t\tlogrus.Errorf(\"userretention: labeler: error getting user: user not found for user attributes %s\", attribs.Name)\n\t\treturn nil\n\t}\n\n\t// Check if user is null before trying to access its Name property\n\tuserName := \"\"\n\tif user != nil {\n\t\tuserName = user.Name\n\t}\n\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"userretention: labeler: error getting user %s: %w\", userName, err)\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `logrus` for logging errors\n- `apierrors` for checking if an error is a 'not found' error\n- `fmt` for formatting error messages\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A1 - Injection](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A1_2017-Injection)\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "63a84067-b748-3163-9448-62bab042eaf2",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability due to Modification of `user` Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference vulnerability due to the modification of the `user` variable. This vulnerability occurs when the program attempts to access a member of a variable that could be `nil`. In this case, if the `Get` method fails and returns an error, the `user` variable could be `nil`. However, the program still attempts to access `user.Name` in the error logging statement, which could lead to a nil dereference panic if `user` is `nil`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always check if a variable is `nil` before attempting to access its members. In this case, you should check if `user` is `nil` before accessing `user.Name` in the error logging statement.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\nuser, err = r.users.Get(user.Name, metav1.GetOptions{})\nif err != nil {\n\tif apierrors.IsNotFound(err) { // The user is no longer, move on.\n\t\treturn nil\n\t}\n\n\tuserName := \"unknown\"\n\tif user != nil {\n\t\tuserName = user.Name\n\t}\n\tlogrus.Errorf(\"userretention: error getting user %s: %v\", userName, err)\n\treturn err\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we first assume that the user's name is \"unknown\". If `user` is not `nil`, we then update the user's name.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `github.com/sirupsen/logrus` for logging.\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1` for `metav1.GetOptions`.\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/api/errors` for `apierrors.IsNotFound`.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A1 Injection](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A1_2017-Injection)\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3725eb83-0220-3349-bc38-83834a776ced",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability due to Modification of `user` Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference vulnerability due to the modification of the `user` variable. This vulnerability occurs when the program attempts to access or modify a member of a structure through a null pointer. In this case, if the `user` object is null, the program will crash when trying to access `user.Name`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always check if an object is null before trying to access or modify its members. This can be done by adding a null check condition before accessing the `user.Name`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nuser, err = l.users.Get(user.Name, metav1.GetOptions{})\nif err != nil {\n    if apierrors.IsNotFound(err) { // The user is no longer, move on.\n        return nil\n    }\n    if user != nil {\n        logrus.Errorf(\"userretention: labeler: error getting user %s: %v\", user.Name, err)\n    } else {\n        logrus.Errorf(\"userretention: labeler: error getting user: %v\", err)\n    }\n    return err\n}\n```\n\nIn the above code, we added a null check for `user` before trying to access `user.Name`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet provided requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `github.com/sirupsen/logrus`\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1`\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/api/errors`\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d30af287-a2c0-38ca-8858-be7701c62b17",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if this function is used to directly write user-controlled input or error messages, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the input will be executed by the browser.\n\nThis vulnerability can be exploited by an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or even take over the user's session.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input or error messages before writing them to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any HTML or JavaScript code.\n\nYou should also implement a Content Security Policy (CSP) to restrict the execution of scripts in your web pages. This can prevent the execution of injected scripts even if an XSS vulnerability is present.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the error message to the HTTP response, you should create a new template, pass the error message to the template, and execute the template. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"error\").Parse(\"<html><body><h1>Error: {{.}}</h1></body></html>\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, err.Error())\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `{{.}}` placeholder in the template will be replaced with the error message, which will be automatically escaped by the `html/template` package.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: Content Security Policy (CSP)](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/Content_Security_Policy)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "37b55e02-2643-38ef-b49e-084f39db0973",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if this function is used to directly write user-controlled input, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the user input will be executed by the browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always sanitize user-controlled input before using it in your application. This can be done by using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any HTML or JavaScript code in the input.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the user-controlled input to the response, you should use the `html/template` package to create a safe HTML template. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"safe\").Parse(ca)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(rw, nil)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.New(\"safe\").Parse(ca)` function creates a new HTML template with the user-controlled input `ca`. The `t.Execute(rw, nil)` function then writes the template to the response, automatically escaping any HTML or JavaScript code in the input.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `html/template` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Go Secure Coding Practices](https://owasp.org/www-pdf-archive/Go_Secure_Coding_Practices_Guide.pdf)\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "75071df0-8b70-33cd-a187-2ca1edaf0ce3",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. However, this function does not perform any HTML escaping, which can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities if user-controlled data is written directly to the response without proper sanitization. XSS vulnerabilities allow an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users, which can lead to a variety of attacks such as stealing user data, performing actions on behalf of the user, or defacing the web page.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done by using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data that is embedded in the HTML template. Additionally, it is also recommended to set the Content-Type header to the appropriate value (e.g., `application/json` for JSON data) to ensure that the browser interprets the response correctly.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of writing the JSON content directly to the response, you should use the `json.Encoder` to encode the data and write it to the response. This ensures that the data is properly formatted as JSON and any special characters are correctly escaped.\n\nHere is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"encoding/json\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(rw http.ResponseWriter, req *http.Request) {\n    // Assume jsonContent is a map or struct that you want to send as JSON\n    encoder := json.NewEncoder(rw)\n    rw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n    err := encoder.Encode(jsonContent)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(rw, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n        return\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "12aa37e3-0538-32a5-8629-db94f7386232",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Increasing Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. However, this function does not perform any HTML escaping, which can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities if user-controlled data is written directly to the response without proper sanitization. XSS vulnerabilities allow an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users, which can lead to a variety of attacks such as stealing user data, performing actions on behalf of the user, or defacing the web page.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done by using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data that is embedded in the HTML template. Additionally, it is also recommended to set the Content-Type header to the appropriate value (e.g., `application/json` for JSON data) to ensure that the browser interprets the response correctly.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of writing the JSON content directly to the response, you should use the `json.Encoder` to encode the data and write it to the response. This ensures that the data is properly formatted as JSON and any special characters are correctly escaped.\n\nHere is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"encoding/json\"\n    \"net/http\"\n)\n\nfunc handler(rw http.ResponseWriter, req *http.Request) {\n    // Assume jsonContent is a map or struct that you want to send as JSON\n    encoder := json.NewEncoder(rw)\n    rw.Header().Set(\"Content-Type\", \"application/json\")\n    err := encoder.Encode(jsonContent)\n    if err != nil {\n        http.Error(rw, err.Error(), http.StatusInternalServerError)\n        return\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "67e15dc0-c9ba-3eb3-9daf-6be0f718a252",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If the data written to the response is not properly sanitized or escaped, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always sanitize and escape any user-supplied input before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the content to the HTTP response, you should use the `html/template` package to render an HTML template with the content. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"name\").Parse(\"<h1>{{.}}</h1>\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(rw, content)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `{{.}}` placeholder in the template is automatically replaced with the content, and any special HTML characters in the content are automatically escaped.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "06c3cf8c-a7de-3bb4-9037-16aadd171461",
              "name": "\"Replace `math/rand` with `crypto/rand` due to Security Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `math/rand` package is used for generating pseudo-random numbers. However, it is not suitable for generating random numbers in a security-sensitive context, as it uses a deterministic source to generate random numbers. This means that if an attacker can predict the seed value, they can predict the sequence of random numbers generated by `math/rand`.\n\nOn the other hand, `crypto/rand` package generates random numbers from sources that a cryptographic algorithm deems as unpredictable, making it suitable for generating random numbers in a security-sensitive context.\n\nUsing `math/rand` instead of `crypto/rand` in a security-sensitive context is a security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, replace `math/rand` with `crypto/rand` in your Go code whenever you need to generate random numbers in a security-sensitive context.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace:\n\n```go\nimport \"math/rand\"\n\nfunc generateToken() string {\n    b := make([]byte, 16)\n    rand.Read(b)\n    return fmt.Sprintf(\"%x\", b)\n}\n```\n\nWith:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/rand\"\n\nfunc generateToken() string {\n    b := make([]byte, 16)\n    _, err := rand.Read(b)\n    if err != nil {\n        log.Fatal(err)\n    }\n    return fmt.Sprintf(\"%x\", b)\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/rand`\n- `fmt`\n- `log`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Randomness](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Randomness)\n- [CWE-338: Use of Cryptographically Weak PRNG](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/338.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-338",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/338.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-338"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6ea0b6c7-633c-351d-9a34-d6cdc7309cee",
              "name": "World-Writable Directory Creation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWorld-Writable Directory Creation Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a security flaw where a directory is created with permissions that allow any user to write to it. This can lead to unauthorized modification of data, data corruption, or even data loss. In the provided code snippet, the `os.MkdirAll` function is used with `os.ModePerm` as the permission argument, which creates a directory that is writable by all users.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should restrict the permissions of the directory to only those users who need to write to it. This can be done by using more restrictive permissions when calling the `os.MkdirAll` function.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nif err := os.MkdirAll(p, 0755); err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this version, the directory is created with 0755 permissions, which means that the owner can read, write, and execute, while others can only read and execute.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- `os` from the standard library\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-276: Incorrect Default Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-276",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-276"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2f14c82b-ac54-3c90-8a15-8757dc2a7e02",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS Configuration, Defaulting to Lower TLS Version",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Missing `MinVersion` in TLS Configuration, Defaulting to Lower TLS Version\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the situation where the minimum version of TLS is not explicitly set in the TLS configuration. This can lead to the use of a lower, potentially insecure version of TLS, which can expose the application to various attacks such as downgrade attacks, where the attacker forces the connection to use a less secure version of TLS.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to explicitly set the `MinVersion` field in the `tls.Config` struct to a secure version of TLS. As of the time of writing, TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3 are considered secure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can set the `MinVersion` field in the `tls.Config` struct:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\nconfig := &tls.Config{\n    MinVersion:         tls.VersionTLS12,\n    InsecureSkipVerify: o.insecure,\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the minimum version of TLS is set to TLS 1.2.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a1c5f9e2-59a5-3fe6-b05a-f783551b0d44",
              "name": "Consider using ReverseProxy.Rewrite over ReverseProxy.Director due to potential header removal vulnerability.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe provided code snippet is a potential security vulnerability in Go programming language. It uses `ReverseProxy.Director` to modify the request headers. However, this approach can lead to header removal vulnerability. An attacker can exploit this vulnerability to bypass security controls by manipulating the headers.\n\nThe vulnerability lies in the fact that the `Director` function is used to delete certain headers from the request. If an attacker can predict or control the headers that are being deleted, they can potentially bypass security controls or inject malicious content.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, consider using `ReverseProxy.Rewrite` instead of `ReverseProxy.Director`. The `Rewrite` function provides a safer way to modify the request headers without the risk of header removal vulnerability.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nRewrite: func(req *http.Request) {\n\treq.URL = logURL\n\treq.Host = logURL.Host\n\tfor key := range req.Header {\n\t\tif strings.HasPrefix(key, \"Impersonate-Extra-\") {\n\t\t\treq.Header.Del(key)\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treq.Header.Del(\"Impersonate-Group\")\n\treq.Header.Del(\"Impersonate-User\")\n\treq.Header.Del(\"Authorization\")\n\treq.Header.Del(\"Cookie\")\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: This package provides HTTP client and server implementations.\n- `strings`: This package implements simple functions to manipulate UTF-8 encoded strings.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top Ten](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/)\n- [CWE-20: Improper Input Validation](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-20",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/20.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-20"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "dd4a884a-d7df-3d32-89ba-c965eb8329fd",
              "name": "World-Writable Directory Creation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWorld-Writable Directory Creation Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a security flaw where a directory is created with permissions that allow any user to write to it. This can lead to unauthorized modification of data, data corruption, or even data loss.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `os.MkdirAll` function is used with `os.ModePerm` as the permission argument. This creates a directory with 0777 permissions, meaning any user can read, write, and execute files in the directory.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should restrict the permissions of the directory to only what is necessary. In most cases, it is sufficient to allow read and write access to the owner only.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code:\n\n```go\nif err := os.MkdirAll(filepath.Dir(path), 0700); err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this version, the directory is created with 0700 permissions, meaning only the owner can read, write, and execute files in the directory.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `os`\n- `path/filepath`\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-276: Incorrect Default Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-276",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-276"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2d817815-85b4-37e5-a1c6-1957ab4cb3c8",
              "name": "\"Filesystem Object Vulnerability due to Direct Application of Archive-Controlled File Mode\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Filesystem Object Vulnerability due to Direct Application of Archive-Controlled File Mode\" in Go programming language occurs when the application directly applies file modes from an archive file to the filesystem without any validation. This can lead to unintended permissions being set, potentially allowing an attacker to gain unauthorized access to sensitive data or execute arbitrary code.\n\nThe specific vulnerability sink in the provided code is the use of `os.FileMode(header.Mode)` to set the file mode directly from the archive file.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to validate the file mode before applying it to the filesystem. This can be done by using a whitelist of allowed file modes, or by applying a mask to the file mode to remove any unwanted permissions.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```go\n// Define a mask to remove unwanted permissions\nconst mask = 0755\n\nf, err := os.OpenFile(target, os.O_CREATE|os.O_RDWR, os.FileMode(header.Mode & mask))\n```\n\nIn this example, the mask `0755` is used to remove any permissions that are not required. This ensures that the file mode applied to the filesystem is always within the expected range.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- `os`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-276: Incorrect Default Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-276",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-276"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "8acb387a-5689-3750-8348-5d126f2d746c",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to send a HTTP response. This function does not perform any HTML escaping, which means that if untrusted data is written directly to the HTTP response, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always HTML escape untrusted data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes data when rendering templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"manifest\").Parse(string(manifestJSON))\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, nil)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, the `template.New()` function is used to create a new HTML template. The `template.Parse()` function is then used to parse the untrusted data, and the `template.Execute()` function is used to write the escaped data to the HTTP response.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go, used for data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f4eb8329-9c36-3ab2-a3a3-c0004a196453",
              "name": "'Fprintf' Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `fmt.Fprintf` function in Go programming language is used to write formatted data to a specified io.Writer. When used with `http.ResponseWriter`, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities if the output is not properly sanitized. This is because `fmt.Fprintf` does not perform HTML escaping, which means that any HTML tags or scripts included in the input will be rendered as-is by the browser, potentially leading to XSS attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always sanitize user input before including it in your output. This can be done by using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any HTML content.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code using `html/template`:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\nt, err := template.New(\"repos\").Parse(`{\"repositories\": [\"{{.}}\", \"{{.}}\", \"{{.}}\"]}`)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\nerr = t.Execute(w, catalog)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this version of the code, the `template.Execute` method automatically escapes any HTML content in the `catalog` slice.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `fmt`\n- `html/template`\n- `net/http`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2caa319e-1dae-3ac5-ae51-d1b2944256c8",
              "name": "'Fprintf' Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `fmt.Fprintf` function in Go programming language is used to write formatted data to a specified io.Writer. When used with `http.ResponseWriter`, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities if the output is not properly sanitized. This is because `fmt.Fprintf` does not perform HTML escaping, which means that any HTML tags or scripts included in the input will be rendered as-is by the browser, potentially leading to XSS attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always sanitize user input before including it in your output. This can be done by using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any HTML content.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the code using `html/template`:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\nt, err := template.New(\"repos\").Parse(`{\"repositories\": [\"{{.}}\", \"{{.}}\", \"{{.}}\"]}`)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\nerr = t.Execute(w, catalog)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this version of the code, the `template.Execute` method automatically escapes any HTML content in the `catalog` slice.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `fmt`\n- `html/template`\n- `net/http`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
