            {
              "id": "2fb9ef33-8491-348d-94ce-84c24b38343d",
              "name": "Insecure SHA1 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe SHA-1 (Secure Hash Algorithm 1) is a cryptographic hash function that takes an input and produces a 160-bit (20-byte) hash value. However, it is considered to be insecure for many cryptographic uses since vulnerabilities were discovered that could lead to collision attacks. This means that two different inputs could produce the same hash output, which is a major security risk.\n\nIn Go programming language, if you are using the `sha1` package to generate hash values, you are exposing your application to potential security risks. It is recommended to use more secure hash functions like SHA-256 or SHA-3 instead.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should replace the usage of SHA-1 with a more secure hash function. The Go standard library provides the `crypto/sha256` and `crypto/sha3` packages for this purpose.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the usage of `sha1` with `sha256` or `sha3`. Here is an example of how to do it:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/sha256\"\n\ndata := []byte(\"your data\")\ndigest := sha256.Sum256(data)\n```\n\nOr with `sha3`:\n\n```go\nimport \"golang.org/x/crypto/sha3\"\n\ndata := []byte(\"your data\")\ndigest := sha3.Sum256(data)\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe Go standard library includes the `crypto/sha256` package, so no additional dependencies are required for it. However, for `sha3`, you need to import the `golang.org/x/crypto/sha3` package.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "aaf82dcd-b308-302f-8e0e-184bed7ba119",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` function is used to send a data response to an HTTP request. However, if this function is used to directly write user-controlled input or error messages, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because the function does not perform HTML escaping, which means that any HTML or JavaScript code included in the input will be executed by the browser.\n\nThis vulnerability can be exploited by an attacker to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or even take over the user's session.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always escape user-controlled input or error messages before writing them to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes any HTML or JavaScript code.\n\nYou should also implement a Content Security Policy (CSP) to restrict the execution of scripts in your web pages. This can prevent the execution of injected scripts even if an XSS vulnerability is present.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing the error message to the HTTP response, you should create a new template, pass the error message to the template, and execute the template. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt, err := template.New(\"error\").Parse(\"<html><body><h1>Error: {{.}}</h1></body></html>\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n\nerr = t.Execute(w, err.Error())\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `{{.}}` placeholder in the template will be replaced with the error message, which will be automatically escaped by the `html/template` package.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `html/template` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: Content Security Policy (CSP)](https://owasp.org/www-community/controls/Content_Security_Policy)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f97832d5-e54c-33bd-a5b5-98dbd815c695",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS configuration with default to lower version than recommended",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `MinVersion` field in the `tls.Config` struct is used to specify the minimum SSL/TLS version that is acceptable. If `MinVersion` is zero, the TLS package will choose the most secure protocol version enabled by both the client and the server. If `MinVersion` is set to a value lower than the recommended version, it may expose the application to vulnerabilities present in the lower versions of SSL/TLS.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to set the `MinVersion` to a secure version of SSL/TLS. As of now, TLS 1.2 and TLS 1.3 are considered secure. Using a lower version like SSL 3.0, TLS 1.0, TLS 1.1 could expose the application to attacks like POODLE, BEAST, etc.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can set the `MinVersion` in the `tls.Config`:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\ntransport.TLSClientConfig = &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs:    certs,\n    MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS12, // Set minimum TLS version to 1.2\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This package implements the TLS (Transport Layer Security) protocol, which provides communication security over the internet.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "fc5f1e32-c856-36b9-8d7e-ef5ac903d707",
              "name": "\"Mitigating XSS Vulnerabilities in Go Web Applications by Using `html/template` for HTML Content Rendering\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, the `text/template` package is often used for generating textual output. However, if user-supplied input is included in the template without proper sanitization, it can lead to XSS vulnerabilities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities in Go web applications, it is recommended to use the `html/template` package instead of `text/template` for rendering HTML content. The `html/template` package ensures that variables are automatically and correctly escaped according to their context within the HTML document.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nIf you are currently using `text/template` like this:\n\n```go\nimport \"text/template\"\n\nfunc renderTemplate(w http.ResponseWriter, tmpl string, p *Page) {\n    t, _ := template.ParseFiles(tmpl + \".html\")\n    t.Execute(w, p)\n}\n```\n\nYou should switch to using `html/template`:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\nfunc renderTemplate(w http.ResponseWriter, tmpl string, p *Page) {\n    t, _ := template.ParseFiles(tmpl + \".html\")\n    t.Execute(w, p)\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`\n- `html/template`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
