            {
              "id": "f49d7a2c-9b14-33fd-a308-065704161910",
              "name": "\"Possible Denial-of-Service Detection through Zip Bomb Attack Mitigated by Limiting Max Bytes Read Using `io.CopyN()`\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `io.Copy()` function is used to copy from a source to a destination until either EOF (End of File) is reached on the source or an error occurs. This function can be exploited in a Denial-of-Service (DoS) attack through a Zip Bomb. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it, by consuming large amounts of system resources. \n\nThe vulnerability arises when an attacker sends a Zip Bomb to the server, and the server uses `io.Copy()` to read the file. Since `io.Copy()` reads until EOF, it will keep reading the Zip Bomb file, consuming a large amount of memory and potentially causing a DoS.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you can use the `io.CopyN()` function instead of `io.Copy()`. The `io.CopyN()` function copies n bytes (or until an error) from the source to the destination. By limiting the maximum bytes read, you can prevent the server from consuming too much memory when reading a Zip Bomb.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nReplace:\n\n```go\nif _, err := io.Copy(f, tr); err != nil {\n```\n\nWith:\n\n```go\nif _, err := io.CopyN(f, tr, maxBytes); err != nil {\n```\n\nWhere `maxBytes` is the maximum number of bytes you want to read.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `io`: The `io` package provides basic interfaces to I/O primitives.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "ea75c36a-2adb-3ea7-ba3d-890235836ee3",
              "name": "\"Integer Sign Change or Downcasting Vulnerability with `int32` Method\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability is related to the conversion of a string to an integer using the `strconv.Atoi` function in Go. If the string represents a number that is too large to fit into an `int`, the function returns the maximum or minimum `int` value, depending on the sign of the number. This can lead to unexpected behavior if the resulting `int` value is then used in a context where its exact value matters.\n\nIn the provided code, the `strconv.Atoi` function is used to convert a string to an integer, which is then used to determine the number of replicas for a deployment. If the string represents a number that is too large to fit into an `int`, the number of replicas could be set to an incorrect value.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should validate the input string before converting it to an integer. You can use the `strconv.ParseInt` function with a bit size of 32 to ensure that the number fits into an `int32`. If the `ParseInt` function returns an error, you should handle it appropriately.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the `strconv.Atoi` function with the `strconv.ParseInt` function as follows:\n\n```go\nnum, err := strconv.ParseInt(numStr, 10, 32)\nif err != nil {\n\t// handle error\n\treturn deployment, nil\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/labels`\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/selection`\n- `k8s.io/api/apps/v1`\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-190: Integer Overflow or Wraparound](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/190.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-190",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/190.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-190"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "29b65641-6292-3cfe-b782-76cc9f4d9da1",
              "name": "Unencrypted HTTP Get Request Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nUnencrypted HTTP Get Request Vulnerability refers to the security risk associated with sending sensitive data over an unencrypted HTTP connection. In the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `http.Get` function is used to send a request to a non-HTTPS URL. This exposes the data sent in the request to potential interception, as the data is not encrypted and can be read by anyone who is able to capture the network traffic.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, always use HTTPS (HTTP Secure) when sending sensitive data. HTTPS encrypts the data sent between the client and the server, making it much more difficult for an attacker to read the data even if they are able to capture the network traffic.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can fix the vulnerability in the provided code:\n\n```go\nresp, err := client.Get(\"https://not-used/ping\")\n```\n\nBy simply changing \"http://\" to \"https://\", the request will now be sent over an encrypted connection.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided uses the `net/http` package from the Go standard library. No additional library dependencies are required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "170a4c20-0ed0-3a4b-a745-184dd4f1e20a",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability in `cluster` Variable Modification",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference vulnerability. This occurs when the `cluster` variable is `nil` and the program tries to access `cluster.Name`. If `cluster` is `nil`, the program will panic and crash, leading to a denial of service.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this issue, you should always check if a variable is `nil` before trying to access its fields or methods. This is especially important when dealing with pointers, interfaces, or other types that can be `nil`.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\ncluster, err = p.Clusters.Update(cluster)\nif err != nil {\n    clusterName := \"\"\n    if cluster != nil {\n        clusterName = cluster.Name\n    }\n    return cluster, fmt.Errorf(\"[reconcileCluster] Failed to update cluster [%s]: %v\", clusterName, err)\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we first check if `cluster` is `nil` before trying to access `cluster.Name`. If `cluster` is `nil`, we use an empty string as the cluster name.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the exact library dependencies. However, it seems to be using a custom package `p.Clusters` which would need to be imported. The `fmt` package is also used, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A2:2017 Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "817c5fc7-3782-3999-bb63-88b950f14525",
              "name": "Insecure SHA1 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe SHA-1 (Secure Hash Algorithm 1) is a cryptographic hash function which takes an input and produces a 160-bit (20-byte) hash value. However, it is considered to be insecure for most cryptographic functions since 2005 as it is vulnerable to collision attacks. In Go programming language, if you are using `sha1.New()` to create a new hash.Hash computing the SHA1 checksum, it is considered as a security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nIt is recommended to use a more secure hash function like SHA-256 or SHA-3. These hash functions are currently not known to have the vulnerabilities that SHA-1 has. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `sha1.New()`, you should use `sha256.New()` or `sha3.New256()` from the `crypto/sha256` or `golang.org/x/crypto/sha3` package respectively.\n\nHere is an example of how to use `sha256`:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/sha256\"\n\nh := sha256.New()\n```\n\nAnd here is an example of how to use `sha3`:\n\n```go\nimport \"golang.org/x/crypto/sha3\"\n\nh := sha3.New256()\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- For SHA-256: `crypto/sha256`\n- For SHA-3: `golang.org/x/crypto/sha3`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "db23e927-22e3-3c03-bd4b-09fb67877894",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic uses because it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, which can lead to security vulnerabilities. In Go programming language, if you are using `md5.New()` to create a new hash, you are potentially exposing your application to these vulnerabilities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe recommended mitigation is to use a more secure hash algorithm, such as SHA256 or SHA3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not susceptible to the same vulnerabilities as MD5.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `md5.New()`, you should use `sha256.New()` or `sha3.New512()` from the `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3` package respectively. Here is an example of how to do this:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n)\n\nfunc secureHash() hash.Hash {\n    return sha256.New()\n}\n```\n\nOr using SHA3:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"golang.org/x/crypto/sha3\"\n)\n\nfunc secureHash() hash.Hash {\n    return sha3.New512()\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code examples require the following library dependencies:\n\n- For SHA256: `crypto/sha256`\n- For SHA3: `golang.org/x/crypto/sha3`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "5000baf2-3cb4-3a56-ad09-b415b4117c09",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic purposes as it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, making it possible for an attacker to craft a malicious input that produces the same hash as a legitimate input. This can lead to a variety of security vulnerabilities, such as password cracking, data integrity attacks, and more.\n\nIn the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package provides functions to compute MD5 hashes. If your application uses this package to compute hashes for cryptographic purposes, it may be vulnerable to the aforementioned attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should replace the MD5 hash algorithm with a more secure hash algorithm, such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not susceptible to hash collisions.\n\nIn Go, you can use the `crypto/sha256` or `crypto/sha3` packages to compute SHA-256 or SHA-3 hashes, respectively.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can replace the MD5 hash algorithm with SHA-256 in your code:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"encoding/hex\"\n    \"time\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    hasher := sha256.New()\n    hasher.Write([]byte(time.Now().String()))\n    uniqueIdentifier := hex.EncodeToString(hasher.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `encoding/hex`\n- `time`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "65c848d1-c7a3-3a21-af27-a8150ee62474",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability due to Modification of `cluster` Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference vulnerability due to the modification of the `cluster` variable. This vulnerability occurs when the `cluster` variable is nil and the program tries to access its `Spec.RKEConfig` field. This can happen if the `h.provisioningClusters.Update(cluster)` function call fails and returns a nil `cluster` and a non-nil `err`. In such a case, the subsequent access to `cluster.Spec.RKEConfig` will cause a runtime panic, leading to a potential denial of service.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always check if a variable is nil before trying to access its fields or methods. In this case, you should check if `cluster` is nil before accessing `cluster.Spec.RKEConfig`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\ncluster, err = h.provisioningClusters.Update(cluster)\nif err != nil {\n\th.migrator.CleanupKnownSecrets(harvesterConfigSecrets)\n\tif cluster != nil {\n\t\tcluster.Spec.RKEConfig = initialRKEConfig\n\t}\n\treturn cluster, err\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we add a nil check for `cluster` before accessing its `Spec.RKEConfig` field.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the exact library dependencies. However, it seems to be using some custom types and methods, which might be defined in the same package or in an external package.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Null Dereference](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Null_Dereference)\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "466e78db-d1f0-306c-8ca3-4f536fb9f290",
              "name": "Code Injection Vulnerability Detected in 'exec.Command' Input",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `exec.Command` function in Go is used to execute system commands. If the input to this function is not properly sanitized, it can lead to a code injection vulnerability. This happens when an attacker is able to inject malicious code as input, which is then executed by the system. This can lead to a variety of security issues, including unauthorized access, data theft, and system damage.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using user input directly in `exec.Command`. If it is necessary to use user input, it should be properly sanitized to remove any potentially harmful code. Additionally, it is recommended to use parameterized functions or prepared statements, which can help prevent code injection.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of passing the entire command as a single string, you should pass the command and its arguments as separate strings. This way, the command interpreter doesn't interpret special characters in the arguments.\n\nHere is a fixed version of your code:\n\n```go\ncmd, err := jailer.JailCommand(exec.CommandContext(ctx, binaryPathInJail, arg1, arg2, arg3), jailPath)\n```\n\nIn this example, `arg1`, `arg2`, and `arg3` are the arguments to the command. They are passed as separate strings, so they won't be interpreted as part of the command.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example provided requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `os/exec`: This is a standard library in Go, used for executing system commands.\n- `context`: This is also a standard library in Go, used for carrying deadlines, cancellation signals, and other request-scoped values across API boundaries and between processes.\n- `jailer`: This is not a standard library and its usage depends on the specific implementation. It is presumably used for creating a restricted environment (jail) for the command execution.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Injection](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Code_Injection)\n- [CWE-94: Improper Control of Generation of Code ('Code Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-94",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/94.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-94"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1f8ed478-60af-3805-b8c6-4528f8280a6b",
              "name": "\"Replace `math/rand` with `crypto/rand` due to Security Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `math/rand` package is used for generating pseudo-random numbers. However, it is not suitable for generating random numbers in a security-sensitive context, as it uses a deterministic source to generate random numbers. This means that if an attacker can predict the seed value, they can predict the sequence of random numbers generated by `math/rand`.\n\nOn the other hand, `crypto/rand` package generates random numbers from sources that a cryptographic algorithm deems as unpredictable, making it suitable for generating random numbers in a security-sensitive context.\n\nUsing `math/rand` instead of `crypto/rand` in a security-sensitive context is a security vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, replace `math/rand` with `crypto/rand` in your Go code whenever you need to generate random numbers in a security-sensitive context.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace:\n\n```go\nimport \"math/rand\"\n\nfunc generateToken() string {\n    b := make([]byte, 16)\n    rand.Read(b)\n    return fmt.Sprintf(\"%x\", b)\n}\n```\n\nWith:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/rand\"\n\nfunc generateToken() string {\n    b := make([]byte, 16)\n    _, err := rand.Read(b)\n    if err != nil {\n        log.Fatal(err)\n    }\n    return fmt.Sprintf(\"%x\", b)\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/rand`\n- `fmt`\n- `log`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Randomness](https://owasp.org/www-community/vulnerabilities/Insecure_Randomness)\n- [CWE-338: Use of Cryptographically Weak PRNG](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/338.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-338",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/338.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
