                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2bdcc7b6-a8f2-36b6-a280-6edae764d773",
              "name": "\"Zip Slip and Unsafe Extraction Vulnerability in Archive Extraction via External Tools (`tar`/`unzip`)\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Zip Slip\" is a widespread arbitrary file overwrite critical vulnerability, which typically results in remote command execution. It was discovered and responsibly disclosed by the Snyk Security team ahead of a public disclosure on 5th June 2018, and affects thousands of projects, including ones from HP, Amazon, Apache, Pivotal and many more. \n\nIn Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when extracting files from an archive without validating that the extraction path is within the desired directory. If an attacker can control the archive's content, they can create files in arbitrary file system locations by using `..` in the file paths.\n\nThe provided code example is vulnerable because it uses the `unzip` command to extract files from an archive without validating the paths of the extracted files.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always validate file paths when extracting files from an archive. You should reject file paths that contain `..` or that resolve to a location outside of the desired directory.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple way to validate file paths in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"archive/zip\"\n    \"path/filepath\"\n    \"strings\"\n)\n\nfunc SafeExtract(input string, temp string) error {\n    r, err := zip.OpenReader(input)\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    defer r.Close()\n\n    for _, f := range r.File {\n        fpath := filepath.Join(temp, f.Name)\n\n        // Check for ZipSlip. More Info: http://bit.ly/2MsjAWE\n        if !strings.HasPrefix(fpath, filepath.Clean(temp)+string(os.PathSeparator)) {\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"%s: illegal file path\", fpath)\n        }\n\n        // ... proceed to extract the file ...\n    }\n\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nThis code opens the archive, iterates over the files, and checks that each file path is within the desired directory.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `os/exec`: for executing the `unzip` command.\n- `archive/zip`: for opening the archive and iterating over the files.\n- `path/filepath`: for manipulating file paths.\n- `strings`: for checking the prefix of the file path.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A5: Broken Access Control](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A5_2017-Broken_Access_Control)\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-22",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-22"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "0ca6e7df-4771-3799-bbff-ca4d7ed7ff3e",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability in `cluster` Variable Modification",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference vulnerability in the `cluster` variable modification. This vulnerability occurs when the `cluster` variable is `nil` and the program tries to access its `RKEConfig` field. If `cluster` is `nil`, this will result in a runtime panic, causing the program to crash.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always check if a variable is `nil` before trying to access its fields or methods. This can be done by adding an `if` statement to check if the variable is `nil`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\ncluster, err = h.provisioningClusters.UpdateStatus(cluster)\nif err != nil {\n\th.migrator.CleanupKnownSecrets(harvesterConfigSecrets)\n\tif cluster != nil {\n\t\tcluster.Spec.RKEConfig = initialRKEConfig\n\t}\n\treturn cluster, err\n}\n```\n\nIn this fix, we added an `if` statement to check if `cluster` is `nil` before trying to access its `RKEConfig` field.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code snippet does not provide enough context to determine the exact library dependencies. However, it seems to be using some custom types and methods, which suggests that it might be part of a larger codebase with its own dependencies.\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "d8452768-1d5a-3c76-b34f-f71df8759c54",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Loading Session/Cookie Secret Material from Secret Management or Environment Instead of Hardcoding in Source Code\" refers to the insecure practice of hardcoding sensitive information such as session or cookie secrets directly into the source code. This is a security risk because if the source code is ever exposed, the hardcoded secrets are also exposed, which could lead to unauthorized access or other security breaches.\n\nIn the provided Go code snippet, the secret key `legacyHashedTokenKey` is hardcoded into the source code:\n\n```go\noldAuthSecret.Data[\"hash\"] = []byte(legacyHashedTokenKey)\n```\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, secrets should never be hardcoded into the source code. Instead, they should be loaded from a secure environment variable or a secret management system. This ensures that even if the source code is exposed, the secrets remain secure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided Go code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// Load the secret from an environment variable\nlegacyHashedTokenKey := os.Getenv(\"LEGACY_HASHED_TOKEN_KEY\")\n\noldAuthSecret.Data[\"hash\"] = []byte(legacyHashedTokenKey)\n```\n\nIn this fixed code, the secret key is loaded from an environment variable named `LEGACY_HASHED_TOKEN_KEY` instead of being hardcoded into the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet and the fixed code snippet only require the standard `os` library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A2: Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-798"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "a9effb1a-52b9-3d93-a2c0-43fe281ed9ca",
              "name": "Missing `MinVersion` in TLS configuration defaults to insecure TLS1.0, set it to a secure version like `VersionTLS13`.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `tls.Config` struct is used to configure a TLS (Transport Layer Security) client or server. If the `MinVersion` field in `tls.Config` is not set, it defaults to TLS 1.0, which is considered insecure due to several known vulnerabilities. This could potentially expose the application to various security risks, including man-in-the-middle attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to set the `MinVersion` field to a secure version of TLS, such as `tls.VersionTLS13`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is how you can set the `MinVersion` field to `tls.VersionTLS13`:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/tls\"\n\ntransport.TLSClientConfig = &tls.Config{\n    RootCAs: pool,\n    MinVersion: tls.VersionTLS13,\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This is a standard library in Go, used for implementing TLS.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "15f3edd1-4a82-3d09-a416-d2120e0fd69e",
              "name": "\"Hardcoded Session/Cookie Secret Material Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Loading Session/Cookie Secret Material from Secret Management or Environment Instead of Hardcoding in Source Code\" refers to the insecure practice of hardcoding sensitive information such as session or cookie secrets directly into the source code. This is a security risk because if the source code is ever exposed, the hardcoded secrets are also exposed, which could lead to unauthorized access or other security breaches.\n\nIn the provided Go code snippet, the secret key `legacyHashedTokenKey` is hardcoded into the source code:\n\n```go\noldAuthSecret.Data[\"hash\"] = []byte(legacyHashedTokenKey)\n```\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, secrets should never be hardcoded into the source code. Instead, they should be loaded from a secure environment variable or a secret management system. This ensures that even if the source code is exposed, the secrets remain secure.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided Go code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"os\"\n\n// Load the secret from an environment variable\nlegacyHashedTokenKey := os.Getenv(\"LEGACY_HASHED_TOKEN_KEY\")\n\noldAuthSecret.Data[\"hash\"] = []byte(legacyHashedTokenKey)\n```\n\nIn this fixed code, the secret key is loaded from an environment variable named `LEGACY_HASHED_TOKEN_KEY` instead of being hardcoded into the source code.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet and the fixed code snippet only require the standard `os` library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017 Category A2: Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-798: Use of Hard-coded Credentials](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-798",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/798.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
