            {
              "id": "8db8c765-c7b3-3257-b3ee-f4c3e3cfe269",
              "name": "Vulnerability in ReverseProxy: Misuse of Director over Rewrite for Header Removal",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Misuse of Director over Rewrite for Header Removal\" in Go's ReverseProxy is a security issue where the `Director` function is misused, leading to potential security risks. The `Director` function is a part of Go's `http.ReverseProxy` and is used to modify the incoming request's URL, headers, or other properties. If not used correctly, it can lead to security vulnerabilities such as information leakage, unauthorized access, or other potential attacks.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `Director` function is used to proxy the request without removing or modifying any headers. This can lead to potential security issues if the headers contain sensitive information.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to properly handle headers in the `Director` function. Sensitive headers should be removed or modified before the request is proxied. This can prevent potential information leakage or unauthorized access.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nDirector: func(req *http.Request) {\n    // Remove sensitive headers\n    req.Header.Del(\"Sensitive-Header\")\n\n    if err := p.proxy(req); err != nil {\n        logrus.Infof(\"Failed to proxy: %v\", err)\n    }\n},\n```\n\nIn this fix, the `Sensitive-Header` is removed before the request is proxied.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: This is a standard library in Go for HTTP client and server implementations.\n- `github.com/sirupsen/logrus`: This is a structured logger for Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-346: Origin Validation Error](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/346.html)\n\nPlease note that the links are valid and active for anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-346",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/346.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-346"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "3801e89c-1c96-3b00-9f07-f70001f17e2f",
              "name": "\"Possible Denial-of-Service Detection through Zip Bomb Attack\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nA Denial-of-Service (DoS) attack is a security event that occurs when an attacker makes it impossible for legitimate users to use a service. This can be achieved through various means, one of which is a Zip Bomb attack. In the context of Go programming language, a Zip Bomb attack can be executed if the application does not properly handle the decompression of zip files. \n\nA Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it. It is often employed to disable antivirus software, in order to create an opening for more traditional viruses. \n\nIn the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the fact that the `io.Copy` function is used to copy data from a tar archive to a gzip writer without any form of validation or size limit. This can lead to a situation where an attacker can send a specially crafted tar file (Zip Bomb) that when decompressed, consumes all available system resources leading to a Denial-of-Service.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to:\n\n1. Implement a size limit for the files that can be decompressed.\n2. Validate the content of the files before decompression.\n3. Use a safer alternative for file decompression that inherently protects against Zip Bomb attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple way to implement a size limit:\n\n```go\nlimitReader := &io.LimitedReader{R: tar, N: maxFileSize}\n\nif _, err := io.Copy(gz, limitReader); err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\nIn this code, `maxFileSize` is the maximum size of file you want to allow. If the file is larger than this, `io.Copy` will return an error.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `io` package from the standard library\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n- [OWASP - File Upload Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/File_Upload_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption ('Resource Exhaustion')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "dba31318-08a5-3e6f-a449-61b828e58780",
              "name": "\"Deserialization into `interface{}` may cause CWE-502 security vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, deserialization of untrusted data into an `interface{}` type can lead to a security vulnerability known as CWE-502: Deserialization of Untrusted Data. This vulnerability occurs when a program deserializes data without properly validating or sanitizing it. An attacker can exploit this vulnerability by providing malicious data that, when deserialized, can lead to arbitrary code execution, denial of service, or other types of attacks.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid deserializing untrusted data whenever possible. If deserialization is necessary, you should use safe, simple data structures and avoid using `interface{}`. You should also validate and sanitize the data before deserializing it.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of deserializing into an `interface{}`, deserialize into a struct that exactly matches the expected JSON structure. For example:\n\n```go\ntype MyStruct struct {\n    Field1 string `json:\"field1\"`\n    Field2 int    `json:\"field2\"`\n    // add more fields as needed\n}\n\nvar result MyStruct\nerr := json.Unmarshal([]byte(annoValue), &result)\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `encoding/json` package from the standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 2017: A8-Insecure Deserialization](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A8_2017-Insecure_Deserialization)\n- [CWE-502: Deserialization of Untrusted Data](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-502",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/502.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-502"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "676953fa-6e63-3ad5-ba21-81182627590a",
              "name": "Non-static command detected in 'exec.Command', potential for code injection vulnerability.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `exec.Command` function is used to execute system commands. If the arguments passed to this function are not properly sanitized, it can lead to a code injection vulnerability. This happens when an attacker is able to inject malicious code as an argument to the `exec.Command` function, which is then executed by the system.\n\nThis vulnerability is often referred to as \"Non-static command detected in 'exec.Command', potential for code injection vulnerability.\"\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to avoid using user input directly in `exec.Command`. If it's necessary to use user input, it should be properly sanitized and validated before being used as an argument in `exec.Command`.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using:\n\n```go\ncmd := exec.Command(name, arg...)\n```\n\nYou should use:\n\n```go\ncmd := exec.Command(name, strings.Fields(arg)...)\n```\n\nThis will ensure that the arguments are properly sanitized before being passed to `exec.Command`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `os/exec`: This is a standard library in Go, used for executing system commands.\n- `strings`: This is also a standard library in Go, used for manipulating strings.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-project-code-review-guide/)\n- [OWASP Go Secure Coding Practices](https://owasp.org/www-pdf-archive/Go_Secure_Coding_Practices_Guide.pdf)\n\n## CWE\n\nThis vulnerability is related to [CWE-78: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an OS Command ('OS Command Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html)."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-78",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-78"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "7f919b3b-298d-302a-99c6-bfc90708c570",
              "name": "\"File Replacement and Local Privilege Escalation Vulnerability due to os.Executable() Behaviour Variation Across Operating Systems\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `os.Executable()` function in Go programming language is used to find the path name for the executable that started the current process. However, there is a vulnerability associated with this function due to its behaviour variation across different operating systems. \n\nIn some operating systems, the function may return a path that points to a symbolic link, instead of the actual executable. If an attacker can replace this symbolic link with a link to a malicious executable, they can escalate their privileges on the system. This is known as a File Replacement and Local Privilege Escalation Vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, developers should avoid using the `os.Executable()` function to determine the location of the current executable. Instead, they should use other methods that are less prone to this type of attack, such as hardcoding the path to the executable or using a configuration file to store the path.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `os.Executable()`, you can use `os.Getwd()` to get the current working directory and then append the known executable name to the path. Here is an example:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"fmt\"\n\t\"os\"\n\t\"path/filepath\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n\tdir, err := os.Getwd()\n\tif err != nil {\n\t\tlog.Fatal(err)\n\t}\n\n\texecPath := filepath.Join(dir, \"known_executable\")\n\tfmt.Println(\"Path to executable:\", execPath)\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, \"known_executable\" should be replaced with the actual name of your executable.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `fmt`\n- `os`\n- `path/filepath`\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [CWE-59: Improper Link Resolution Before File Access ('Link Following')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/59.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are active and accessible to anonymous users at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-59",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/59.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-59"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "9c23b8d3-ce53-38a6-ad3c-122a180053c6",
              "name": "\"Mitigating XSS Vulnerabilities in Go Web Applications by Using `html/template` for HTML Content Rendering\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nCross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript. XSS allows attackers to execute scripts in the victim's browser which can hijack user sessions, deface web sites, or redirect the user to malicious sites.\n\nIn Go programming language, using `text/template` for HTML content rendering can lead to XSS vulnerabilities because it does not automatically escape HTML content. This means that if user input is included in the HTML without being properly escaped, an attacker could inject malicious scripts.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate XSS vulnerabilities in Go web applications, use the `html/template` package instead of `text/template` for HTML content rendering. The `html/template` package ensures that variables are automatically and correctly escaped, according to the context.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```go\nimport \"text/template\"\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n```\n\nAnd then make sure to use this package when rendering HTML content.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe Go standard library includes the `html/template` package, so no additional library dependencies are required.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "47fb65bd-c48f-3eac-8a33-e881ec7c624b",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure due to its vulnerability to collision attacks, where two different inputs produce the same hash output. This can lead to various security issues such as data integrity violation and unauthorized information disclosure. In Go programming language, if you are using `md5.New()` to create a new hash, you are using the insecure MD5 hash algorithm.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nIt is recommended to use a more secure hash algorithm such as SHA256 or SHA3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not vulnerable to collision attacks. They provide a higher level of security and are recommended for most use cases.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the MD5 hash algorithm with SHA256 or SHA3. Here is an example of how to use SHA256 in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"fmt\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    h := sha256.New()\n    h.Write([]byte(\"your data\"))\n    fmt.Printf(\"%x\", h.Sum(nil))\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe above code requires the following standard library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `fmt`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
