            {
              "id": "2ac643d8-699e-3dad-859f-913e32f30666",
              "name": "'printf' Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities. Use 'html/template' for User Data Rendering.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `fmt.Sprintf` function is used to format and return a string without printing it anywhere. When this function is used in conjunction with `http.ResponseWriter.Write()`, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because `fmt.Sprintf` does not escape HTML characters, which means that any user-supplied input can potentially include malicious scripts that will be executed in the browser of any user viewing the rendered HTML.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use the `html/template` package for user data rendering. This package automatically escapes any HTML characters, preventing the possibility of XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of:\n\n```go\nrw.Write([]byte(fmt.Sprintf(\"%s\\n\", level)))\n```\n\nUse:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\ntmpl, err := template.New(\"test\").Parse(\"{.}\\n\")\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\nerr = tmpl.Execute(rw, level)\nif err != nil {\n    // handle error\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `fmt`\n- `net/http`\n- `html/template`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP XSS Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "379bf44a-13cd-3cdd-9563-dc28ea4477d2",
              "name": "\"Non-static command detected in 'exec.Command': Potential Code Injection Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `exec.Command` function is used to execute system commands. If the arguments passed to this function are not properly sanitized, it can lead to a potential code injection vulnerability. This happens when an attacker is able to control the input to the `exec.Command` function, which can lead to the execution of arbitrary commands on the system where the Go application is running.\n\nThis vulnerability is particularly dangerous because it can lead to a complete system compromise. The attacker could potentially execute any command on the system with the same privileges as the Go application.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should avoid using user-controlled input as arguments to the `exec.Command` function. If this is not possible, you should properly sanitize the user input before passing it to the function. This can be done by using a whitelist of allowed characters, or by escaping special characters that could be used to inject arbitrary commands.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly passing user-controlled input to the `exec.Command` function, you should use a static string as the command to be executed, and pass the user-controlled input as arguments to this command. Here is an example:\n\n```go\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(processContext, \"/bin/sh\", \"-c\", r.Path + \" \" + port)\n```\n\nIn this example, the command to be executed is `/bin/sh -c`, and the user-controlled input is passed as an argument to this command. This ensures that the user-controlled input is treated as a single argument, and not as part of the command to be executed.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `os/exec`: This is a standard library in Go, used for executing system commands.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Code Review Guide](https://owasp.org/www-project-code-review-guide/)\n- [CWE-78: Improper Neutralization of Special Elements used in an OS Command ('OS Command Injection')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-78",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/78.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-78"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "12d1adff-1d30-3859-80a6-98059d999477",
              "name": "'printf' Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Potentially Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities. Use 'html/template' Package for User Data Rendering.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe `printf` function in Go's `fmt` package is detected in the `http.ResponseWriter.write()` method. This can bypass HTML escaping and potentially lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an application includes untrusted data in a new web page without proper validation or escaping, or updates an existing web page with user-supplied data using a browser API that can create HTML or JavaScript.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the error message is directly included in the response without any sanitization or escaping. If the error message contains any user-controlled input, this could lead to a potential XSS vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use the `html/template` package for user data rendering. This package automatically escapes any data that is rendered, preventing potential XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"error\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(\"Failed to parse form: {{.}}\\n\")\nt.Execute(rw, err)\n```\n\nIn this version, the error message is rendered using the `html/template` package, which automatically escapes any data that is rendered.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: Provides HTTP client and server implementations.\n- `html/template`: Provides data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "24ef8e88-beec-35f7-8d28-a427e6146e8b",
              "name": "'printf' Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities: Use 'html/template' Package for User Data Rendering Instead.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `fmt.Sprintf` function is used to format and return a string without printing it anywhere. When this function is used in conjunction with `http.ResponseWriter.Write()`, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. This is because `fmt.Sprintf` does not escape HTML characters, which means that if user-supplied data is included in the string being formatted, it could include malicious scripts that will be executed when the resulting string is rendered in a web browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use the `html/template` package for rendering user data. This package automatically escapes any HTML characters in the data, preventing the possibility of XSS attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `fmt.Sprintf` and `http.ResponseWriter.Write()`, use `html/template` to render the data. Here is how you can modify the code:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nt := template.New(\"error\")\nt, _ = t.Parse(\"Failed to parse loglevel: {{.}}\\n\")\nt.Execute(rw, err)\n```\n\nIn this code, `t.Parse` is used to create a new template that includes the error message, and `t.Execute` is used to render this template directly to the `http.ResponseWriter`, with `err` as the data.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `html/template`: This is a standard library in Go, used for data-driven templates for generating HTML output safe against code injection.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "294b8d7d-521a-3698-8b8f-7ee4418823cc",
              "name": "Insecure gRPC Server Vulnerability due to Lack of Encryption and Credentials",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure gRPC Server Vulnerability due to Lack of Encryption and Credentials is a security vulnerability that occurs when a gRPC server is created without any form of encryption or credentials. This leaves the server open to unauthorized access and data interception. This vulnerability is particularly relevant in Go programming language where gRPC servers are often used for inter-service communication.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always use encryption and authentication when creating a gRPC server. This can be achieved by using Transport Layer Security (TLS) for encryption and token-based authentication for verifying the identity of clients.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to create a secure gRPC server with TLS and token-based authentication:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"google.golang.org/grpc\"\n    \"google.golang.org/grpc/credentials\"\n)\n\n// Load the certificates from disk\ncert, err := tls.LoadX509KeyPair(\"server.crt\", \"server.key\")\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatalf(\"could not load server key pair: %s\", err)\n}\n\n// Create a TLS-based credential\ncreds := credentials.NewServerTLSFromCert(&cert)\n\n// Create a gRPC server object\ns.grpcServer = grpc.NewServer(grpc.Creds(creds))\n```\n\nIn this example, `server.crt` and `server.key` are the server's certificate and private key respectively. These files should be securely stored and accessible only by the server.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- google.golang.org/grpc\n- google.golang.org/grpc/credentials\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP gRPC Security](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/gRPC_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "85bcb93e-24e0-389d-b441-b4c420604962",
              "name": "\"Potential Zip Slip and Unsafe Extraction Vulnerability in Archive Extraction via External Tools (`tar`/`unzip`)\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Potential Zip Slip and Unsafe Extraction Vulnerability in Archive Extraction via External Tools (`tar`/`unzip`)\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a scenario where an attacker can craft a malicious archive that, when extracted, can overwrite arbitrary files and directories within the file system. This can lead to arbitrary code execution, privilege escalation, or denial of service.\n\nThe vulnerability arises from the use of external tools like `tar` or `unzip` for archive extraction without proper validation of the file paths in the archive. The `exec.Command` function in Go is used to execute these external commands, and if the input to these commands is not properly sanitized, it can lead to this vulnerability.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use a library for archive extraction that properly validates file paths and prevents path traversal attacks. Additionally, avoid using external tools for archive extraction when possible, as they may not provide the necessary security controls.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of using `exec.Command` to run `tar`, you can use the `archive/tar` package in Go to extract the tar archive. This package provides the necessary controls to prevent path traversal attacks.\n\nHere is an example of how you can use the `archive/tar` package to extract a tar archive:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"archive/tar\"\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n    \"path/filepath\"\n    \"strings\"\n)\n\nfunc untar(tarball, target string) error {\n    reader, err := os.Open(tarball)\n    if err != nil {\n        return err\n    }\n    defer reader.Close()\n\n    tarReader := tar.NewReader(reader)\n\n    for {\n        header, err := tarReader.Next()\n        if err == io.EOF {\n            break\n        } else if err != nil {\n            return err\n        }\n\n        path := filepath.Join(target, header.Name)\n        info := header.FileInfo()\n\n        if info.IsDir() {\n            if err = os.MkdirAll(path, info.Mode()); err != nil {\n                return err\n            }\n            continue\n        }\n\n        file, err := os.OpenFile(path, os.O_CREATE|os.O_TRUNC|os.O_WRONLY, info.Mode())\n        if err != nil {\n            return err\n        }\n        defer file.Close()\n\n        if _, err := io.Copy(file, tarReader); err != nil {\n            return err\n        }\n    }\n\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following Go standard library packages:\n\n- `os`\n- `io`\n- `path/filepath`\n- `archive/tar`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Path Traversal](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Path_Traversal)\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-22",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-22"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c20c2d99-f118-3b0b-9e35-6897131623e0",
              "name": "Insecure gRPC Server Vulnerability due to Lack of Encryption and Credentials",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nInsecure gRPC Server Vulnerability due to Lack of Encryption and Credentials is a security vulnerability that occurs when a gRPC server is created without any form of encryption or credentials. This leaves the server open to unauthorized access and data interception. This vulnerability is particularly relevant in Go programming language where gRPC servers are often used for inter-service communication.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always use encryption and authentication when creating a gRPC server. This can be achieved by using Transport Layer Security (TLS) for encryption and token-based authentication for verifying the identity of clients.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to create a secure gRPC server with TLS and token-based authentication:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"google.golang.org/grpc\"\n    \"google.golang.org/grpc/credentials\"\n)\n\n// Load the certificates from disk\ncert, err := tls.LoadX509KeyPair(\"server.crt\", \"server.key\")\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatalf(\"could not load server key pair: %s\", err)\n}\n\n// Create a TLS-based credential\ncreds := credentials.NewServerTLSFromCert(&cert)\n\n// Create a gRPC server object\ns.grpcServer = grpc.NewServer(grpc.Creds(creds))\n```\n\nIn this example, `server.crt` and `server.key` are the server's certificate and private key respectively. These files should be securely stored and accessible only by the server.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- google.golang.org/grpc\n- google.golang.org/grpc/credentials\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP gRPC Security](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/gRPC_Security_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)\n\nPlease note that the links provided are valid and active at the time of writing this report."
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-319"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "f86bb1b2-9ff8-37f0-812d-81d78d23ee43",
              "name": "World-Writable Directory Creation Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nWorld-Writable Directory Creation Vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a security flaw where a directory is created with permissions that allow any user to write to it. This can lead to unauthorized modification of data, data corruption, or even data loss.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the `os.MkdirAll` function is used to create a directory with `0777` permissions. This means that the directory is readable, writable, and executable by all users.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should restrict the permissions of the directory to only those users who need access. This can be done by setting the permissions to `0700` (only the owner can read, write, and execute), `0755` (owner can read, write, and execute; others can only read and execute), or another appropriate value.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed code:\n\n```go\nerr := os.MkdirAll(kontainerdriver.DriverDir, 0700)\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library:\n\n- `os` from the standard Go library\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-276: Incorrect Default Permissions](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-276",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/276.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-276"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b1986e4b-e8f4-3d5a-ac1a-73ae74d624e8",
              "name": "Mutex Unlock Omission Vulnerability",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nMutex Unlock Omission Vulnerability in Go programming language is a type of concurrency vulnerability that occurs when a programmer forgets to unlock a mutex after a critical section of code has been executed. This can lead to a deadlock situation where other goroutines are unable to acquire the mutex, causing the program to hang indefinitely.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always use the `defer` statement to unlock a mutex. This ensures that the mutex will be unlocked even if a panic occurs in the critical section of code. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is an example of how to fix this vulnerability:\n\n```go\npackage main\n\nimport (\n\t\"sync\"\n)\n\nvar mu sync.Mutex\n\nfunc criticalSection() {\n\tmu.Lock()\n\tdefer mu.Unlock()\n\n\t// Critical section of code...\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `defer` statement is used to ensure that the mutex `mu` is always unlocked after the critical section of code is executed.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-667: Improper Locking](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/667.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-667",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/667.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-667"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c6c38fe9-65e3-3e89-abeb-71f9c0cf29a5",
              "name": "Potential Nil Dereference Vulnerability due to Modification of `secret` Variable",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe code snippet provided is vulnerable to a potential nil dereference vulnerability due to the modification of the `secret` variable. This vulnerability occurs when the program attempts to access or modify a memory location through a pointer that points to a `nil` or `null` value. In this case, the `secret` variable is being accessed after a potential error condition, which could lead to a nil dereference if the `secret` is `nil`.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always check if a pointer is `nil` before accessing or modifying its value. This can be done by adding an additional condition to check if the `secret` variable is `nil` before accessing its `Name` property.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a recommended fix for the code:\n\n```go\nsecret, err := secretClient.Get(ctx, secretRef.Name, metav1.GetOptions{})\nif err != nil {\n\t// During the encryption key update this can fail for deleted secrets.\n\t// This manifests as an Internal Error from K8s.\n\t// In this case, we can ignore it and let a secret be created.\n\tif !apierrors.IsInternalError(err) {\n\t\treturn nil, fmt.Errorf(\"could not get secret for service account: %w\", err)\n\t}\n\tif secret != nil {\n\t\tlogrus.Infof(\"internal error when getting a secret %s - not using the secret\", secret.Name)\n\t}\n\treturn nil, nil\n}\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies to execute properly:\n\n- `context`\n- `fmt`\n- `github.com/sirupsen/logrus`\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1`\n- `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/api/errors`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Top 10 - A2:2017 Broken Authentication](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A2_2017-Broken_Authentication)\n- [CWE-476: NULL Pointer Dereference](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-476",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/476.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-476"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "c0fc2787-86a6-3410-a411-2e1d506d4ac0",
              "name": "\"Insecure MinVersion of TLS Configuration Objects Detected\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Insecure MinVersion of TLS Configuration Objects Detected\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure configuration of the minimum version of the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol. In the provided code snippet, the minimum version of TLS is set to `tls.VersionTLS10`, which is considered insecure. This is because older versions of TLS, such as TLS 1.0 and 1.1, have known vulnerabilities and are not recommended for secure communications.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should set the `MinVersion` field of the `tls.Config` struct to `tls.VersionTLS12` or `tls.VersionTLS13`. These versions of TLS are currently considered secure and are recommended for secure communications.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is the fixed version of the provided code snippet:\n\n```go\nreturn &tls.Config{\n\tNextProtos:   []string{\"http/1.1\"},\n\tMinVersion:   tls.VersionTLS12,\n\tCertificates: []tls.Certificate{cert},\n\tRootCAs:      certPool,\n}, nil\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/tls`: This package provides the `tls.Config` struct and the `tls.VersionTLS12` constant.\n- `crypto/x509`: This package provides the `x509.Certificate` type.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "2a3f8487-01f3-348f-b0b0-990cbf7bd892",
              "name": "\"Possible Denial-of-Service Detection via Zip Bomb Attack: Mitigation Using `io.CopyN()`\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Go programming language has a vulnerability that can lead to a Denial-of-Service (DoS) attack via a Zip Bomb. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it, because its actual size far exceeds the declared size in the archive metadata. \n\nThe vulnerability lies in the `io.Copy()` function, which is used to copy data from a source to a destination. If the source is a Zip Bomb, the function will continue to read data until the source is exhausted, potentially consuming all available system resources and causing a DoS condition.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you can use the `io.CopyN()` function instead of `io.Copy()`. The `io.CopyN()` function copies a specified number of bytes (N) from the source to the destination. By limiting the amount of data that can be read from the source, you can prevent a Zip Bomb from consuming all system resources.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is an example of how to use `io.CopyN()` to mitigate this vulnerability:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    src, _ := os.Open(\"source.zip\")\n    dst, _ := os.Create(\"destination.zip\")\n    _, err := io.CopyN(dst, src, 1024*1024) // copy only 1MB of data\n    if err != nil {\n        // handle error\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, only 1MB of data is copied from the source to the destination. If the source is a Zip Bomb, it will not be able to consume more than 1MB of system resources.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption ('Resource Exhaustion')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "de9c1a22-d11a-3c1f-83c6-89a249e84e5c",
              "name": "\"Possible Denial-of-Service Detection via Zip Bomb Attack: Mitigation Using `io.CopyN()`\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Go programming language has a vulnerability that can lead to a Denial-of-Service (DoS) attack via a Zip Bomb. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it, because its actual size far exceeds the declared size in the archive metadata. \n\nThe vulnerability lies in the `io.Copy()` function, which is used to copy data from a source to a destination. If the source is a Zip Bomb, the function will continue to read data until the source is exhausted, potentially consuming all available system resources and causing a DoS condition.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you can use the `io.CopyN()` function instead of `io.Copy()`. The `io.CopyN()` function copies a specified number of bytes (N) from the source to the destination. By limiting the amount of data that can be read from the source, you can prevent a Zip Bomb from consuming all system resources.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is an example of how to use `io.CopyN()` to mitigate this vulnerability:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nfunc main() {\n    src, _ := os.Open(\"source.zip\")\n    dst, _ := os.Create(\"destination.zip\")\n    _, err := io.CopyN(dst, src, 1024*1024) // copy only 1MB of data\n    if err != nil {\n        // handle error\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, only 1MB of data is copied from the source to the destination. If the source is a Zip Bomb, it will not be able to consume more than 1MB of system resources.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption ('Resource Exhaustion')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
