            {
              "id": "76228fc2-5e44-3175-878a-831f8ed792ca",
              "name": "User-Input Crafted HTTP Redirect Vulnerability Detected",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\n\"User-Input Crafted HTTP Redirect Vulnerability Detected\" is a security vulnerability that occurs when an application accepts user-controlled input and uses this input in a server-side redirect. This can allow an attacker to craft a URL that, if clicked, may redirect users to an arbitrary website where they could be subject to phishing attacks, or the downloading and execution of malicious code.\n\nIn the Go programming language, this vulnerability can occur when the `http.Redirect` function is used with unvalidated user input.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to validate all user inputs before using them in server-side functions. Specifically, for URLs, it is advisable to check if the URL is in a list of trusted URLs before redirecting. \n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple fix for the specific vulnerability sink:\n\n```go\ntrustedUrls := map[string]bool{\n    \"http://trusted1.com\": true,\n    \"http://trusted2.com\": true,\n    // add more trusted URLs here\n}\n\nu, err := url.ParseRequestURI(userInput)\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatal(err)\n}\n\n_, exists := trustedUrls[u.String()]\nif !exists {\n    log.Fatal(\"URL is not trusted\")\n}\n\nhttp.Redirect(rw, req, u.String(), http.StatusFound)\n```\n\nIn this code, we first parse the user input to a URL. Then we check if the URL exists in our map of trusted URLs. If it does not exist, we log an error and stop the execution. If it does exist, we proceed with the redirection.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `net/http`: for the `http.Redirect` function and `http.StatusFound` constant.\n- `net/url`: for the `url.ParseRequestURI` function.\n- `log`: for the `log.Fatal` function.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Unvalidated Redirects and Forwards Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Unvalidated_Redirects_and_Forwards_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-601: URL Redirection to Untrusted Site ('Open Redirect')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-601",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/601.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-601"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "47d31b31-48cc-30ce-bbf2-24ed4d1aeb90",
              "name": "\"Potential Denial-of-Service Attack Detected via Zip Bomb: Mitigation Possible by Limiting Max Bytes Read\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe Go programming language has a vulnerability that can lead to a potential Denial-of-Service (DoS) attack via a Zip Bomb. A Zip Bomb is a malicious archive file designed to crash or render useless the program or system reading it, because its actual size far exceeds the declared size in the archive metadata. This is a form of DoS attack. The vulnerability arises when the Go program reads an archive file without limiting the maximum number of bytes read.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to limit the maximum number of bytes read from the archive file. This can be achieved by wrapping the `tarReader` with `io.LimitReader`, which effectively limits the number of bytes read to a specified limit.\n\n## Source Code Fix\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to limit the maximum number of bytes read:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"io\"\n    \"os\"\n)\n\nconst MaxReadBytes = 1 << 20 // 1MB, adjust as needed\n\nfunc main() {\n    // Assume file and tarReader are defined elsewhere\n    var file *os.File\n    var tarReader io.Reader\n\n    limitedReader := io.LimitReader(tarReader, MaxReadBytes)\n    _, err := io.Copy(file, limitedReader)\n    if err != nil {\n        // handle error\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, `io.LimitReader` is used to limit the number of bytes read from `tarReader` to `MaxReadBytes`.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following Go standard library packages:\n\n- `io`\n- `os`\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Denial of Service](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Denial_of_Service)\n- [CWE-400: Uncontrolled Resource Consumption ('Resource Exhaustion')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-400",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/400.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-400"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "1bcf1b6f-0815-3d61-a206-8763e8462f35",
              "name": "Direct Writing Detected in 'http.ResponseWriter.write()', Bypassing HTML Escaping and Leading to Cross-Site Scripting Vulnerabilities",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nIn Go programming language, the `http.ResponseWriter.Write()` function is used to write data to the HTTP response. If user-controlled data is directly written to the HTTP response without proper sanitization or encoding, it can lead to Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. XSS vulnerabilities occur when an attacker is able to inject malicious scripts into web pages viewed by other users. These scripts can steal sensitive information, perform actions on behalf of the user, or exploit other vulnerabilities in the user's browser.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to always HTML escape user-controlled data before writing it to the HTTP response. This can be done using the `html/template` package in Go, which automatically escapes user-controlled data when rendering HTML templates.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nInstead of directly writing user-controlled data to the HTTP response, use the `html/template` package to render HTML templates. Here is an example:\n\n```go\nimport \"html/template\"\n\n// ...\n\nfunc handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {\n    t, _ := template.ParseFiles(\"template.html\")\n    data := map[string]string{\n        \"UserControlledData\": r.URL.Query().Get(\"data\"),\n    }\n    t.Execute(w, data)\n}\n```\n\nIn this example, the `template.html` file should contain `{{.UserControlledData}}` where the user-controlled data should be inserted. The `html/template` package will automatically HTML escape the data.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- The `net/http` package, which is part of the standard library in Go.\n- The `html/template` package, which is also part of the standard library in Go.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP: Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/xss/)\n- [OWASP: XSS (Cross Site Scripting) Prevention Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cross_Site_Scripting_Prevention_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-79: Improper Neutralization of Input During Web Page Generation ('Cross-site Scripting')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-79",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/79.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-79"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "6b9ac3fb-768e-3baa-9320-0baf35299671",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic uses due to its vulnerability to collision attacks. In a collision attack, an attacker can generate two different inputs that hash to the same output, which can lead to various security issues. Therefore, it is recommended to use a more secure hash algorithm such as SHA256 or SHA3.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should replace the MD5 hash algorithm with a more secure one, such as SHA256 or SHA3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not vulnerable to collision attacks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the MD5 hash algorithm with SHA256 or SHA3. Here is an example of how to do this in Go:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"crypto/sha256\"\n    \"io\"\n)\n\nhasher := sha256.New()\nio.WriteString(hasher, \"your string to hash\")\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256`\n- `io`\n\n## OWASP Resources\n\n- [OWASP Cryptographic Storage Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Cryptographic_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [OWASP Hashing Java](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Password_Storage_Cheat_Sheet.html#hashing-java)\n\n## Common Weakness Enumeration (CWE)\n\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "29cbc18f-2fdc-31bf-9524-f27ad3ca5781",
              "name": "\"Insecure MinVersion TLS Configuration Object Creation Detection\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Insecure MinVersion TLS Configuration Object Creation Detection\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure configuration of the minimum version of TLS (Transport Layer Security) in the `tls.Config` object. In the provided code, the minimum version of TLS is set to `tls.VersionTLS10`, which is considered insecure. This is because TLS 1.0 is known to have several weaknesses and vulnerabilities, and its use is deprecated. Using this version of TLS can expose the application to various attacks, such as BEAST, CRIME, and POODLE attacks.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should set the minimum version of TLS to a more secure version, such as `tls.VersionTLS12` or `tls.VersionTLS13`. These versions of TLS have improved security features and are not vulnerable to the attacks that affect TLS 1.0.\n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is the recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```go\ncfg: &tls.Config{\n    MinVersion:   tls.VersionTLS12,\n    CipherSuites: []uint16{tls.TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384, tls.TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256},\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "278b6842-7bae-3767-b527-9673eaee1fa9",
              "name": "\"Insecure MinVersion TLS Configuration Object Creation Detection\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Insecure MinVersion TLS Configuration Object Creation Detection\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to the insecure configuration of the minimum version of the Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol. In the provided code snippet, the minimum version of TLS is set to `tls.VersionTLS11`, which is considered insecure. This is because TLS 1.1 and earlier versions have known vulnerabilities and are deprecated. Using these versions can expose the application to various security risks, including man-in-the-middle attacks.\n\n## Mitigation\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should set the minimum version of TLS to `tls.VersionTLS13` or `tls.VersionTLS12` as they are currently the most secure versions. \n\n## Code Fix\n\nHere is the recommended fix for the provided code:\n\n```go\ncfg: &tls.Config{\n    MinVersion:   tls.VersionTLS13,\n    CipherSuites: []uint16{tls.TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_AES_256_GCM_SHA384, tls.TLS_ECDHE_ECDSA_WITH_CHACHA20_POLY1305_SHA256},\n},\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the `crypto/tls` package from the Go standard library.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-326: Inadequate Encryption Strength](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-326",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/326.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-326"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "5cb0a6e9-d974-3f9b-a5a4-80c4ac64b4ed",
              "name": "Insecure MD5 Hash Algorithm Detected, Use SHA256 or SHA3 Instead",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe MD5 hash algorithm is considered insecure for many cryptographic purposes as it is susceptible to hash collisions. This means that two different inputs can produce the same hash output, making it possible for an attacker to craft a malicious input that produces the same hash as a legitimate input. This can lead to a variety of security vulnerabilities, such as password cracking, data integrity attacks, and more.\n\nIn the Go programming language, the `crypto/md5` package is used to compute the MD5 hash of a given input. If this package is used in a security-critical context, it could expose the application to the aforementioned vulnerabilities.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nThe recommended mitigation is to replace the use of the MD5 hash algorithm with a more secure hash algorithm, such as SHA-256 or SHA-3. These algorithms are currently considered secure and are not susceptible to the same vulnerabilities as MD5.\n\nIn Go, the `crypto/sha256` and `crypto/sha3` packages can be used to compute the SHA-256 and SHA-3 hashes, respectively.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nReplace the use of `md5.Sum` with `sha256.Sum256` or `sha3.Sum256`:\n\n```go\nimport \"crypto/sha256\"\n\ndigest := sha256.Sum256([]byte(machine.RequestedHostname))\n```\n\nor\n\n```go\nimport \"golang.org/x/crypto/sha3\"\n\ndigest := sha3.Sum256([]byte(machine.RequestedHostname))\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `crypto/sha256` or `golang.org/x/crypto/sha3` for the SHA-256 or SHA-3 hash functions, respectively.\n\n## References\n\n- [OWASP - Insecure Cryptographic Storage](https://owasp.org/www-project-top-ten/2017/A3_2017-Sensitive_Data_Exposure)\n- [CWE-327: Use of a Broken or Risky Cryptographic Algorithm](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-327",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/327.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-327"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "b1510410-5875-32c6-aac7-82fecfe496ae",
              "name": "\"Prevent Zip Slip and Path Traversal by Validating Extraction Paths in Archive Extraction\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Prevent Zip Slip and Path Traversal by Validating Extraction Paths in Archive Extraction\" vulnerability in Go programming language refers to a security flaw where an attacker can manipulate the file paths in an archive file (like a zip or tar file) to overwrite important files or create new ones in unexpected locations when the archive is extracted. This can lead to unauthorized access, data corruption, or even remote code execution.\n\nThe vulnerability sink in the provided code is the `os.OpenFile` function, which is used to open a file with the specified name and mode. If the `filePath` variable is not properly validated, it can lead to the mentioned security issues.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, you should always validate the extraction paths before extracting an archive. This can be done by checking if the extraction path is within the expected directory. If it's not, the extraction should be aborted.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a simple way to validate the extraction path in Go:\n\n```go\ncleanPath := filepath.Clean(filePath)\nif !strings.HasPrefix(cleanPath, expectedDir) {\n    return fmt.Errorf(\"invalid file path: %s\", filePath)\n}\n\nfile, err := os.OpenFile(cleanPath, os.O_CREATE|os.O_TRUNC|os.O_WRONLY, info.Mode())\n```\n\nIn this code, `filepath.Clean` is used to eliminate any \"..\" or similar path traversal sequences from the `filePath`. Then, `strings.HasPrefix` is used to check if the cleaned path starts with the expected directory. If it doesn't, an error is returned.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following standard library dependencies:\n\n- `os`\n- `fmt`\n- `strings`\n- `path/filepath`\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Path Traversal](https://owasp.org/www-community/attacks/Path_Traversal)\n- [CWE-22: Improper Limitation of a Pathname to a Restricted Directory ('Path Traversal')](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-22",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/22.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-22"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "664b9bb0-b7e4-31c6-82ef-5c906410018b",
              "name": "\"Application of Archive-Controlled File Mode to Filesystem Objects Vulnerability\"",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe \"Application of Archive-Controlled File Mode to Filesystem Objects Vulnerability\" in Go programming language is a security issue that arises when the file permissions or modes for a filesystem object are set based on user-controlled input. This can lead to unauthorized access or privilege escalation if a malicious user is able to manipulate the input to set the file permissions to a more permissive mode than intended.\n\nIn the provided code snippet, the vulnerability arises from the use of `os.FileMode(header.Mode)` where `header.Mode` is potentially user-controlled input from an archive file.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to not rely on user-controlled input to set file permissions. Instead, explicitly set the file permissions to a secure default, and only allow changes to the permissions through a secure administrative interface that includes proper authentication and authorization checks.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nA potential fix for the provided code snippet would be to replace `os.FileMode(header.Mode)` with a constant representing the desired file permissions. For example, to set the permissions to 0755 (read and execute access for everyone and also write access for the owner of the file), you could modify the code as follows:\n\n```go\nerr = os.MkdirAll(filePath, 0755)\n```\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe provided code snippet requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- `os`: The built-in Go library for operating system functionality.\n\n## References\n\n- [CWE-732: Incorrect Permission Assignment for Critical Resource](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/732.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-732",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/732.html"
                  }
                ],
                "severity": "MEDIUM",
                "kind": "FAIL",
                "tags": [
                  "CWE-732"
                ]
              }
            },
            {
              "id": "231b9694-09c0-3bb4-bd2d-6f6db08528f5",
              "name": "Insecure gRPC client credentials vulnerability due to improper TLS usage.",
              "helpUri": "https://www.glog.ai/",
              "help": {
                "text": "",
                "markdown": "## Description\n\nThe vulnerability \"Insecure gRPC client credentials due to improper TLS usage\" in Go programming language arises when the gRPC client is configured to use insecure transport credentials. This can lead to a variety of security issues, including man-in-the-middle attacks, where an attacker can intercept and potentially alter the communication between the client and the server.\n\n## Mitigation Advice\n\nTo mitigate this vulnerability, it is recommended to use secure transport credentials when dialing a gRPC server. This can be achieved by using `credentials.NewClientTLSFromCert` or `credentials.NewTLS` functions from the `google.golang.org/grpc/credentials` package, which create secure transport credentials from a given certificate or TLS configuration respectively.\n\n## Source Code Fix Recommendation\n\nHere is a code snippet that demonstrates how to use secure transport credentials:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    \"google.golang.org/grpc\"\n    \"google.golang.org/grpc/credentials\"\n)\n\ncreds, err := credentials.NewClientTLSFromFile(certFile, \"\")\nif err != nil {\n    log.Fatalf(\"Failed to create TLS credentials %v\", err)\n}\nconn, err := grpc.Dial(addr, grpc.WithTransportCredentials(creds))\n```\n\nIn this example, `certFile` is the path to the client's certificate file.\n\n## Library Dependencies\n\nThe code example requires the following library dependencies:\n\n- google.golang.org/grpc\n- google.golang.org/grpc/credentials\n\n## OWASP and CWE Links\n\n- [OWASP Transport Layer Protection Cheat Sheet](https://cheatsheetseries.owasp.org/cheatsheets/Transport_Layer_Protection_Cheat_Sheet.html)\n- [CWE-319: Cleartext Transmission of Sensitive Information](https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html)"
              },
              "properties": {
                "cwe": [
                  {
                    "id": "CWE-319",
                    "url": "https://cwe.mitre.org/data/definitions/319.html"
